<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Sets up Elite Anti-Crime Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- An FBI-style special
investigative unit, dubbed the Scorpions, was officially launched
in South Africa Wednesday, local media reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launching, President Thabo Mbeki said the
200-strong unit had the ability to beat crime and the government
would be watching for results.
</P>
<P>
Super cop Frank Dutton will head the unit, whose official name
is the Directorate of Special Investigations.
</P>
<P>
Dutton said his brief was to produce a dedicated pool of
skilled professionals with the resources and capacity to
effectively combat organized and syndicate crime, serious economic
offenses, corruption in the criminal justice system and crimes
against the state.
</P>
<P>
"Although I am excited about the future of the Scorpions, I am
certainly under no illusion as to the enormity of the task we
face. I accept the position with some trepidation," he said.
</P>
<P>
He cautioned that there were no quick fix solutions.
</P>
<P>
"What we aim to achieve will take some time to establish. We
want to develop a skilled and dedicated investigations capacity.
We intend to start out with an initial staff component of about
200 people, and hope to grow to a full complement of approximately
2,000 members over the next two years. "
</P>
<P>
Dutton emphasized that the Scorpions would not replace existing
law enforcement structures but would aim to complement and
reinforce existing efforts.
</P>
<P>
Dutton's new team will report directly to National Director of
Public Prosecutions Bulelani Ngcuka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
