<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Relocate Major Settlements of Quake-hit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit said here Wednesday that the government has started to
consider relocating at least three major settlements battered by
the August 17 earthquake.
</P>
<P>
Receiving Nasuh Mahruki, leader of Turkey's Search and Rescue
Society, Ecevit said geological conditions must be take into
account in planning new settlements, adding that settlements
established in natural disaster-prone areas should be relocated to
safer places.
</P>
<P>
Admitting that many of the settlements and industrial
establishments were built in high-risk quake or flood areas,
Ecevit said it was impossible to correct the situation overnight
but the country must act immediately to avoid future mishaps.
</P>
<P>
He hinted that at least three of the nine major settlements
battered by the killer quake, namely Adapazari, Golcuk and
Degirmender, will be reconstructed in safer locations.
</P>
<P>
On August 17, a 7.4-magnitude quake hit populous northwestern
Turkey, killing over 14,000 people, injuring 24,000 others and
leaving over 500,000 people homeless. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
