<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Africa Predicts Half Mln AIDS-Related Deaths in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Projections showed that
the number of AIDS-related deaths in South Africa would increase
from 200,000 in the year 2000 to half-a-million in 2010, South
African Health Minister Manto Tshabalala-Msimang said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Replying to a question by a member of parliament from an
opposition party, she said the short and medium-term projections
were based on data from past and current trends in the HIV
epidemic.
</P>
<P>
Longer projections were considered of little value due to the
complex and relatively unknown dynamics affecting the future
spread of HIV which causes AIDS, she said.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Education Minister Kader Asmal
Wednesday released a policy document which bans discrimination
against pupils, students and teachers who disclose they are
HIV-positive or have AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The policy did not compel pupils, students and teachers with
HIV or AIDS to disclose this fact to the authorities.
</P>
<P>
However, any affected person would be free to disclose such
information voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
According to the document, "appropriate measures" must be taken
where the affected person poses a health risk to others.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear what these measures are.
</P>
<P>
The policy also emphasizes life-skills training and stipulates
that pupils, students and teachers must receive education about
HIV and AIDS on an ongoing basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
