<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Trade With Rest of Africa Booming: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's exports to
the rest of Africa now total some 20 billion rand (3.3 billion
U.S. dollars) a year, according to a report released Wednesday by
the United Nations news agency, IRIN, in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
This indicated an expansion of 335 percent since 1992 when
trade sanctions against South Africa were lifted.
</P>
<P>
The report, compiled by a research group for South Africa's
export promotion trade fair, Saitex, showed that most of South
Africa's export trade was in manufactured goods.
</P>
<P>
The figures however excluded exports to South Africa's partners
in the Southern African Customs Union that comprise Botswana,
Lesotho, Namibia and Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
It was not all good news. The figures also showed a sharp
slowdown in the growth of this trade in the last three years.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the export trade had grown by 61 percent from 1992,
while in 1996 the figure stood at only a 27 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 export trade grew by only 11 percent and last year a
mere three percent growth was recorded.
</P>
<P>
This decline, according to the report, was partly because of
the worldwide recession and also because of the unresolved trade
dispute with South Africa's main neighboring market of Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The trade dispute between the two countries, it said, revolved
around the trade deficit which favors South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe imports goods worth about 325 million dollars per
annum from South Africa, while South Africa imports from Zimbabwe
goods worth only about 75 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report said there was a fall last year of 15 percent in
South Africa' s imports from the rest of Africa, which was "bound
to create political tensions within the region". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
