<HEADLINE> 61 Bodies Rescued from Argentine Plane Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENAS AIRES, September 1 (Xinhua) -- A total of 61 bodies have
been recovered, up to midday (local time) Wednesday, in the area
of the Jorge Newberry airport of Buenas Aires, where a Boeing 737
passenger jet crashed on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, the bodies, of which only 7 have
been identified, have been taken to the judicial mortuary.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the job of identification is very
difficult, as many of the remains were delivered in bags and are
practically carbonized.
</P>
<P>
One official source confirmed that the black box from the
aircraft has been found, and that it has been passed on to the
National Aircraft Accident Board so that the cause of the accident
may be determined.
</P>
<P>
The Boeing 737, belonging to the LAPA company, with 95
passengers and 5 crew members, crashed on take-off Tuesday evening
then burst into flames in a collision with a golf course club
house which was situated opposite the airport.
</P>
<P>
The local press, on Wednesday morning, reduced the number of
dead from more than 80 on Tuesday evening, including both
passengers and people on the ground, to more than 60. However they
said that the total number of victims is still unknown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
