<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7 Lebanese Killed in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Two Lebanese civilians and
five members of the pro-Israeli South Lebanon Army (SLA) were
killed Wednesday in clashes between Israeli troops and Lebanese
guerrillas, according to Lebanese security sources.
</P>
<P>
The five SLA militiamen were killed by a roadside bomb near
the Labbaya village in the western Bekka Valley which borders the
Israeli occupied border zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, claimed
responsibility for the explosion.
</P>
<P>
In response, Israeli artillery troops blasted the village,
killing two villagers identified as Hassan Akel, 22, and Fatmeh
Jabali, 25. Another five civilians were also wounded in the
shelling.
</P>
<P>
Israeli warplanes also raided several suspected Hezbollah
targets in the occupied zone which was set up in 1985 by Israel
to protect its north from Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border
attacks.
</P>
<P>
But there has been no immediate casualties reports from the
Israeli air raids.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Hezbollah warned that if one more Lebanese civilian
was attacked by Israeli fire it would fire Katyusha rockets into
northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
"I want to tell the (Israeli) settlers to be ready as of today
to go to bomb shelters any time a Lebanese civilian is
wounded," Hezbollah's second-in-command Naim Kassem said at a
funeral procession held in Beirut for a Hezbollah fighter.
</P>
<P>
He also said Hezbollah would not take the impending Middle East
tour by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright into
consideration when it picks the time and venue for launching
Katyusha missiles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
