<HEADLINE> Iraqi Civilian Targets Bombed by U.S.-British </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. and British warplanes on
Wednesday bombed some civilian and service installations in
northern Iraq while a U.S. congressional delegation is in Iraq
for a visit, said an Iraqi military spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 11:05 (0705 GMT) seven formations
of U.S. and British warplanes coming from a Turkish base violated
northern Iraqi airspace over Dohuk, Erbil and Neineva provinces.
</P>
<P>
These enemy planes bombed some civilian facilities in Mosul,
the capital city of Neineva province, said the spokesman. He did
not mention whether casualties were caused or not.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iraqi anti-aircraft units fired missiles at the
enemy planes and repulsed them to their base in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and British warplanes coming from Saudi and Kuwaiti bases
also violated southern Iraqi airspace in the day, said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the U.S. congressional delegation,
which arrived here on Sunday to assess the humanitarian
consequences of nine years of U.N. sanctions, visited a children
hospital in southern Iraqi province of Misan.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. delegation was received on Tuesday by Iraqi Deputy
Prime Minister Tariq Aziz. One member of the delegation said they
had a "useful, interesting, productive and warm discussion" with
Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Since last December's airstrikes against Iraq, U.S. and
British warplanes have been targetting Iraqi civilian and military
targets in the no-fly zones, causing severe civilian casualties
and property damage.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones were imposed on Iraq by the U.S.-led western
allies following the 1991 Gulf War with the claimed aim of
protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the
south against attacks by Iraqi government troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
