<HEADLINE> Turkish President Vetos New Amnesty Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel Wednesday vetoed the controversial amnesty law pushed
through the parliament last Satruday by the coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Now the law goes back to the parliament to be re-debated in
October when the legislation returns from its current recess.
</P>
<P>
The law came under strong criticism from legal experts, the
judiciary and police authorities.
</P>
<P>
In his letter to the parliament, Demirel said he feels the
principles of equality in the Constitution have been violated by
the amnesty law.
</P>
<P>
He said that the amnesty has "in a way given exceptional
treatment to those who set up gangs to commit a crime."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that a total of 58,518 prisoners would benefit
from the new amnesty law which will cover the crimes committed
before April 23,1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
