<HEADLINE> U.S. Registered Plane Downed in Ethiopia: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- An aircraft, which was
shot down by Ethiopian anti-craft forces on August 29, has been
identified as a jet registered in the United States.
</P>
<P>
According to a government press release issued on Monday, the
U.S. registered plane was downed after it had entered a no-fly
zone while flying through Ethiopian air space near the northern
town of Adwa, about 40 kilometers of the Eritrean border.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian civil aviation authority designated the northern
part of Ethiopia where the jet was flying as a no-fly zone since
Ethio-Eritrean War started in May last year.
</P>
<P>
All aircrafts that pass through Ethiopian air space should
follow the civil aviation route, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Following the downing, the Ethiopian government sent an
airforce rescue team to the site of the crash. The rescue team
retrieved the remains of a pilot and a co-pilot, who are british
and Swedish nationals respectively.
</P>
<P>
Their remains will soon be brought to Addis Ababa, the capital
of Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian government has informed the British and Swedish
embassies. Further investigation is continuing, the release said.
</P>
</TEXT>
