<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ivanov: Russia Regards Abkhazia as Integral Part of Georgia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov
said here Wednesday that Russia regards Abkhazia as an integral
part of Georgia and that the results of a planned referendum in
the breakaway region will not alter Moscow's stance.
</P>
<P>
"Russia, just as the whole world community, does not recognize
Abkhazia's independence proclaimed in the constitution adopted (by
the separatists) in November 1994," Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
"A referendum, scheduled for October 3 this year, if it is
held, will not change our position," the Itar-Tass news agency
quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Abkhazia is an autonomous region within Georgia. Ethnic
Abkhazis launched a bloody military campaign and, by late 1993,
had gained control of much of the region. A cease-fire providing
for Russian peacekeepers was signed in Moscow May 14, 1994.
</P>
<P>
Georgia has decided to prolong the Russian peacekeepers'
presence in the region, a decision Ivanov welcomed as
satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
"For many years, Russian servicemen have been on a dangerous
peacekeeping mision in Abkhazia. Peace has been maintained in the
conflict zone, to a greater extent, thanks to their efforts," the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
"The political status of Abkhazia must be determined on the
basis of agreements of the sides involved in the conflict, during
the talks, which are conducted with Russia's participation under
U.N. auspices," Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
"The decision of the Abkhazian authorities to hold a referendum
may have a negative effect on the process of the settlement of the
Georgian-Abkhazian conflict," he said.
</P>
<P>
Citing a U.N. Security Council resolution adopted July 30 this
year, Ivanov described a planned presidential election in Abkhazia
as "unacceptable and illegal." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
