<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Minister Optimistic Over Deal With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Minister in Prime
Minister's Office Haim Ramon said Wednesday he was optimistic that
Israel and the Palestinians could reach agreement on the
implementation of the Wye interim agreement.
</P>
<P>
Ramon made the statement after two hours of talks with senior
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat at a Jerusalem hotel.
</P>
<P>
The talks were held after the negotiations between Erekat and
his Israeli counterpart Gilad Sher broke down earlier Wednesday
over the release of Palestinian prisoners and a target date for
the conclusion of the final status talks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's office issued a statement
after the breakdown, demanding the Palestinians to come up with a
satisfactory proposals before the start of a security meeting
Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
After the gaps narrowed in rounds of talks, the Palestinians
demand that Israel release 400 political prisoners, those jailed
for anti-Israel activities, but Israel insists that it will
release only 350.
</P>
<P>
Israel has proposed that the two sides reach a framework on the
final-status talks, which deal with thorny issues like the
Palestinian statehood and Jerusalem, in February 2000 and a
comprehensive agreement in December that year.
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinians want the final agreement to be reached in
April, 2000.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have hoped that Barak and Palestinian National
Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat would be able to sign a
memorandum on the revised Wye agreement at a ceremony in Egypt
Thursday, in the presence of Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and
United States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who started a
visit to the region Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
