<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Hails Signing of Lusaka Cease-fire for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Rwanda Wednesday hailed the
signing of the Lusaka accord on Tuesday by founding members of the
main Congolese rebel movement, the Congolese Rally for Democracy
(RCD).
</P>
<P>
"This is a positive step toward ending the civil war in Congo,
which could pave the way to peace and stability in the region,"
the Rwanda News Agency (RNA) quoted government spokesman, Wilson
Rutayisire, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Rwanda which negotiated the accord, and
signed it, is fully committed to its implementation.
</P>
<P>
As for the military situation in the wake of the signing of the
Lusaka deal, Rutayisire said Rwandan troops are at a standstill,
and will remain in their positions until the U.N. peace-keeping
force is deployed.
</P>
<P>
On pulling out of the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC),
Rutayisire said, "those genocidal forces should be disarmed and
neutralized before any talk of pulling our troops out of Congo."
</P>
<P>
When the RCD launched the rebellion to remove Congolese
President Laurent Kabila from power on August 2 last year, Rwanda
committed troops to helping the rebels, with the aim of doing away
with the Hutu extremist forces which were using the Congolese
territory as a launching pad for their cross- border raids inside
Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 10,000 "Interahamwe" militiamen were reportedly
airlifted from areas in the east of the Congo for training,
reorganization, in its southeastern Katanga province.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of this force constitutes the backbone of the support
to Kabila' s loyalist forces which are also strongly backed by
troops from Zimbabwe, Angola, and Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that the issue of Rwandan Hutu extremists in
the Congo, as well as other regional guerrilla forces operating on
the side of Kabila constitutes the hardest bit of the accord to
chew.
</P>
<P>
There have been allegations by RCD rebels that Kabila has
already started distributing the Congolese identity papers to the
militia which have been fighting for him, thus saving them from
any arrest, disarming, or handing over to Rwanda or to the
International Tribunal in Arusha, northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
These allegations, however, have not been independently
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
Another obstacle people have foreseen is the capacity of the
25,000 U.N. peace-keepers expected to be deployed to disarm the
"Interahamwe" scattered in the Congolese jungle forests for they
will not offer themselves gratuitously, even if they were
operating under Chapter VII.
</P>
<P>
"The signing of the Lusaka accord is one thing, but many
problems remain ahead to have it successfully implemented," one
political analyst, who spoke on anonymity condition, said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Host Hearing in Preparation for U.N.  Millennium Assembly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese Government
will host the hearing for the Asia and Pacific region in
preparation for the Millennium Assembly and Millennium Summit of
the United Nations, the General Assembly announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The hearing will bring together representatives of members and
civil society of the Economic and Social Commission for Asia and
the Pacific (ESCAP).
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo hearing will follow the regional hearings held for
West Africa, Africa, Europe, and the Latin America, and Caribbean
regions.
</P>
<P>
These meetings have been organized at the initiative of the
U.N. Secretary-General, Kofi Annan, and in full cooperation with
the Japanese Executive Secretaries concerned, to provide a forum
for discussing the issues expected to be before the Millennium
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Nabutaka Machimura, Japanese state secretary for foreign
affairs, will officially open the hearing for the Asia and Pacific
region on September 9 at the United Nations University, based in
Tokyo, the General Assembly said.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day open meetings, participants will discuss how
best can the United Nations address the challenges of the 21st
century in the areas of peace and security, economic and social
development, human rights and good governance, and how to
strengthen the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Annan will draw upon the outcome of the regional hearings in
the preparation of his report on the Millennium Assembly to be
issued by March 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
