<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President Stresses Role of Private </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe said Wednesday that the government recognizes the
indispensable role the private sector is capable of playing in the
provision of quality infrastructure in the country.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said this when commissioning the Bulawayo-Beitbridge
railway line at Umzingwane Bridge of west Zimbabwe, the Zimbabwe
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The railway line which started working three months ago had led
to the reduction in rail distance between Beitbridge and Bulawayo,
the second largest city of the country, by more than 200
kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The railway line set aside 15 percent share holding for the
National Railways of Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said there were many opportunities for the private
sector to enter into joint ventures or partnerships with the
government to improve the country's infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The president said through its new economic policy, Zimbabwe
made an undertaking to involve more private sector participants in
key sectors of the economy.
</P>
<P>
He said in line with economic reforms that were taking place in
the rail, road, power and civil aviation transport sub-sectors,
the government had decided to reorient itself in order to
concentrate more on regulating them.
</P>
<P>
The president said the reorientation would result in
facilitating investment, ensuring fair competition and provision
of quality services.
</P>
<P>
"The railway line will not only enhance national economic
growth, but it will also help to foster regional economic growth
and trade, particularly with South Africa," Mugabe added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
