<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ratings Assigned to Industrial Bank of Korea: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 1 (Xinhua) - Fitch IBCA, the international
rating agency assigned Wednesday Short-and Long-term ratings to
Industrial Bank of Korea (IBK) of 'F2' and 'BBB' respectively.
</P>
<P>
It assigned the same Long-and Short-term ratings to IBK as to
the Republic of Korea. The bank is 98 percent government-owned and
operates under a special law, the Industrial Bank of Korea Act.
</P>
<P>
In the same way as for the Korea Development Bank, there is a
provision in this law, which requires the government to make good
any losses incurred by the bank and not covered by its own
reserves.
</P>
<P>
Although this does not amount to an explicit guarantee of
specific liabilities of the bank, it means that the government is
legally obliged to maintain the bank's solvency.
</P>
<P>
In Fitch IBCA's opinion this means that in practice the
government will ensure that the bank is able to meet its
obligations in a timely manner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
