<HEADLINE> Ugandan Minister to Assess Landslide Damages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Minister of Disaster
Preparedness and Refugees Tom Butime will travel to the eastern
district of Mbale to assess the devastating landslide that killed
18 people Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The minister, together with some other senior officials from
the government, is expected to further take relief food to those
made homeless by the disaster, Radio Uganda reported on Wednesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, a total of 14 bodies have been
recovered and buried by their respective families. Some bodies
were so damaged that it was difficult for recognition, the report
added.
</P>
<P>
The landslide, triggered by a downpour in the previous night,
killed 18, mostly children under the age of 12, and left over 300
homeless. The district authorities called on the displaced to live
in places accessible to first aid and other living necessities.
</P>
<P>
The continuing rain hampered the rescue efforts which had
already been made hard with the washing away of makeshift bridges
on the rivers there.
</P>
<P>
Another landslide in the same area killed 35 people and left
over 2,000 homeless in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
