<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Replaces Its Troops in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) Wednesday held a hand-over ceremony at the
Rinas Airport for its forces in Albania, at which new NATO forces
called "Communication Zone West (COMMZW)" replaced its old troops
on "humanitarian" missions in Albania called "AFOR".
</P>
<P>
AFOR and the Albanian government had faced tremendous
challenges of Kosovo refugees during the Kosovo crisis and AFOR
extended significant assistance to the Albanian government and the
Albanian people, said Admiral James Ellis, commander of NATO's
Allied Forces for South Europe.
</P>
<P>
Speaking highly of AFOR's "humanitarian" role, AFOR also
contributed a great deal to the ending of the Kosovo crisis, said
Ellis who arrived here specially for attending the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a speech at the ceremony, Albanian Defense Minister
Juan Hajdaraga said that AFOR has successfully completed its
"humanitarian" missions in Albania and he expressed thanks for
AFOR's assistance to Albania.
</P>
<P>
Stressing Albania would not forget the assistance that AFOR
extended to Albania during the past more than four months,
Hajdaraga said that the Albania government will give support to
COMMZW'S operations in Albania.
</P>
<P>
AFOR Commander Gen. John Reith said that 25 countries
participating in AFOR missions made enormous contribution in
helping the Albanian government to copy with the refugee crisis
and helping ending the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said that the deployment of COMMZW shows that NATO will
continue its presence in Albania.
</P>
<P>
The new COMMZW Commander Gen. Pietro Frisone pledged that he
would do his best to lead his forces to carry out well the
missions of COMMZW in Albania.
</P>
<P>
According to AFOR press officers, the main task of COMMZW,
which means NATO's communication zone west of Kosovo, is to
provide logistic support to NATO peacekeeping forces in Kosovo,
including ensuring the roads leading to Kosovo, while it will help
rehabilitate infrastructure in Albania.
</P>
<P>
AFOR Commander Reith early this week said that Albania has very
various suitable zones for shooting grounds and military
exercises, his remarks implied that COMMZW might have a mission
for conducting training exercises in Albania in the future.
</P>
<P>
AFOR came into Albania in mid-April during the Kosovo crisis.
Its first contingent of some 270 French soldiers arrived on April
12 and its main body moved into the country On April 20.
</P>
<P>
COMMZW will be under the command of Gen. Mickael Jackson,
commander of NATO's forces in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
