<HEADLINE> Russia Criticizes Summers' Remarks on IMF Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 1 (Xinhua) -- A ranking Russian official said
Wednesday that he is bewildered by U.S. Treasury Secretary
Lawrence Summers' statement that Washington will not support the
extension of new IMF credits to Russia until a report on the use
of earlier loans is forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
"I am not sure at the moment what Summers wants to check," the
Interfax news agency quoted Alexander Livshits, the Russian
president's special envoy in international financial institutions,
as saying at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
The use of earlier IMF funds has been reviewed and the findings
of the review made public, he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the IMF team now in Moscow is supportive of the
Russian Cabinet's monetary and economic policy, Livshits said.
</P>
<P>
The PriceWaterhouseCoopers auditing company has already
published its findings on the activities of the Bank of Russia, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"I would love to know what more the U.S. treasury secretary
wants to check," Livshits said.
</P>
<P>
Summers' statement came amid Western media reports on alleged
money laundering by Russian mobsters through several U.S. bank
accounts. Some newspapers said IMF loans could be involved.
</P>
<P>
Livshits said that he does not understand the "game" or why or
by whom it was started. He said he was surprised to see his name
mentioned in a number of articles.
</P>
<P>
"Every country faces problems, but nobody should be allowed to
humiliate Russia. This scandal will not be easy to forget," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Also on Wednesday, Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said Russia
would not tolerate Western attempts to slander the country.
</P>
<P>
Moscow will not accept the "use of unverified facts to cast a
shadow on our country," Ivanov told students at the Moscow Foreign
Relations Institute.
</P>
<P>
Corruption does exist and is a problem, he said, but this
manner of discussing it in "some Western mass media is not
fighting corruption but targeted politics," he said.
</P>
<P>
The scandal surrounding "Russian money laundering" is in effect
the policy "of certain circles, which do not want Russia to
reclaim its role as a great power in the international arena," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said the scandal might be linked "to the election
campaigns underway in Russia and the United States." 
</P>
</TEXT>
