singles, was challenged by Chew Alvin of Malaysia. After trailing
0-13 in the first set, the more experienced Taufik rallied to beat
his rival through his experiences with a 17-14 victory. In the
second set, Taufik made no mistake, beating Chew Alwin by 15-9.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's Haryanto Arbi, who just won Singapore Open
champion, entered the second round by beating Daniel Eriksson from
Sweden with 15-3, 15-3.
</P>
<P>
Marleve Mainaky, Indra Wijaya, Rony Agustinus, Endra Feriyanto,
all from Indonesia, also entered the second round by beating their
rivals, respectively.
</P>
<P>
In the men's singles, 13 of the world's 20 top players are
ready to take up the challenge.
</P>
<P>
Around 250 players from 13 countries and regions are competing
the tournament in Denpasar, about 1,000 kilometers east of here.
The countries include Netherlands, Belgium, Denmark, Germany,
Sweden, Malaysia, Thailand, Italy, Singapore, Finland, Japan,
Brunei and host Indonesia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
