<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Construction Spending Drops in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Commerce Department
reported Wednesday that U.S. construction spending declined 0.5
percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 695.7 billion
dollars in July.
</P>
<P>
Construction spending in June also fell slightly instead of
previously estimated 0.5 percent gain, according to the revised
government figures.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said July's spending decrease was unexpected and
signaled one of the economy's strongest sectors is beginning to
slow.
</P>
<P>
Home building and other construction activity were a key
contributing factor to the strong economic growth in the early
part of the year.
</P>
<P>
In order to slow down the economy and prevent inflation, the
Federal Reserve last week bumped up interest rates by a quarter of
a point, making borrowing more expensive.
</P>
<P>
Rising mortgage rates took a bite out of the housing market in
July. Existing-home sales dropped 3.9 percent, while sales of new
homes increased a slight 0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Today's report showed that spending on all private construction
projects fell 0.7 percent in July, following a tiny increase in
June. Private construction totaled 545 billion dollars, on a
seasonally adjusted annual basis. However, spending on hotels and
motels, and office buildings showing increases.
</P>
<P>
Spending on government projects rose 0.3 percent to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 150.7 billion dollars, after
falling slightly in June. Government spending on schools and other
educational facilities, conservation and development systems and
water supply plants all showed decreases.
</P>
<P>
The report said spending on all residential projects fell 0.8
percent in July to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 319
billion dollars with spending on single-family homes down while
spending on apartments was up. 
</P>
</TEXT>
