<HEADLINE> Turkey to Set Up Prefabricated Buildings for Quake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Minister of Public
Works and Housing Koray Aydin said here on Wednesday that Turkey
would spend about 200 million U.S. dollars to set up prefabricated
buildings for the earthquake victims.
</P>
<P>
Aydin told reporters that Provincial Bank General Directorate
will form the infrastructure for these temporary settlements,
adding that the cost of 50,000 prefabricated residences will be
around 200 million U.S. dollars, which will be met by the Disaster
Fund.
</P>
<P>
He said, "we decided on a standard price in order to include
all firms which are active in this field."
</P>
<P>
The quake survivors will be hosted temporarily at prefabricated
apartments before they move to their permanent residences, said
the minister, adding that his ministry had started looking for
fields to erect prefabricated buildings near cities.
</P>
<P>
Aydin pointed out, "we will start contacting with firms and
signing agreements tomorrow. We have already inspected all firms
one by one. We know their capacity and what they could do." But
he declined to disclose the names of the firms which will build
prefabricated residences. 
</P>
