<HEADLINE> U.S. Open Draw Wide Open As Sampras, Rafter Withdraw </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- In a span of 13 hours, the
men's draw of the U.S. Open was torn wide open when it lost top
seed Pete Sampras of the United States and two-time defending
champion Patrick Rafter of Australian due to injuries.
</P>
<P>
Play had hardly begun at 11 a.m. today when the shocking news
came that Sampras, who was seeking his record 13th Grand Slam
title and fifth U.S. Open championship, had withdrawn with a
strain in his lower back.
</P>
<P>
Rafter brought an abrupt and painfully early end to his hopes
for a third straight title when he retired in the fifth set of his
featured night match against Cedric Pioline of France with an
aching right shoulder that has bothered him all summer.
</P>
<P>
Although second-seeded Andre Agassi now must be considered the
favorite, the top half of the 128-player men's draw is wide open
and devoid of superstars.
</P>
<P>
"It's tough for the tournament," Rafter said, "especially with
Peter playing such great tennis and my form was pretty good as
well coming into here. I was feeling pretty confident about having
some good wins here."
</P>
<P>
Sampras suffered the injury Sunday during a practice session
with Gustavo Kuerten of Brazil. He had been the hottest player on
the men's tour, winning Wimbledon for the sixth time and taking 24
consecutive matches and four titles before withdrawing with a hip
injury during a match against fellow American Vincent Spadea two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
The fourth-seeded Rafter won the first two sets against
Pioline,topping out his serve at 117 miles per hour -- which may
have taken its toll. He received treatment on several occasions
for his ailing shoulder, which had sidelined him since his
withdrawal in Indianapolis less than two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
"It is a sharp pain," admitted Rafter, who became the first
defending men's singles champion in the 119-year history of the
tournament to retire in a first-round match. "I felt it mostly on
my serve, and occasionally when returning his serve on my backhand.
"
</P>
<P>
Tim Henman of Britain became the first casualty among the top
men. The sixth seed was ousted 7-6 (7-1), 6-4, 6-3 by Guillermo
Canas of Argentina. Canas, who is ranked 68th in the world, was 0-
5 on hard courts this year before the upset.
</P>
<P>
Second-seeded Lindsay Davenport opened defense of her title by
eliminating doubles partner and fellow Amercian Corina Morariu 6-0,
6-3 in a day match.
</P>
<P>
Five other seeded men's players were in action Tuesday and
13th seed Alex Corretja of Spain is headed home after being beaten
by Wayne Arthurs of Australia.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere, the fifth-seeded Kuerten beat Bohdan Ulihrach of
the Czech Republic 6-4, 6-4, 6-3; No. 7 Todd Martin of the United
States avoided a five-set meltdown and held off Stephane Huet of
France 6-4, 6-7 (2-7), 6-7 (5-7).7-6 (7-3) in a four-hour match.
No. 16 Nicolas Kiefer of Germany fought off Jason Stoltenberg of
Australia 6-4, 6-3, 1-6, 4-6, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
On the women's side, two-time champion and fourth seed Monica
Seles of the United States routed Germany's Barbara Rittner 6-1,6-
1. Fifth seed Mary Pierce of France ousted Yugoslavia's Sandra
Nacuk 6-3, 7-5; No. 9 Julie Halard-Decugis of France beat Cara
Black of Zimbabwe 6-3, 5-7, 6-3; No. 14 Sandrine Testud of France
and No.16 Conchita Martinez of Spain also beat their rivals
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Serena Williams of the United States needed only 49 minutes to
beat countrywoman Kimberly Po 6-1, 6-0.  
</P>
</TEXT>
