<HEADLINE> GCC Citizens Allowed to Invest in Qatar's Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Citizens of the other five
Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states will be allowed to invest in
Qatar's health sector, a GCC official said in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The GCC General Secretariat was informed of the Qatari decision
through a letter by Assistant Secretary General of the Qatari
Financial and Economic Ministry Sheikh Hamad Bin Faisal Al-Thani,
said Ajlan Al-Kawari, GCC Assistant Secretary General for
Financial Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Qatar will allow the GCC nationals residing in Qatar to invest
in hospitals, specialized clinics, sports medicine, mental therapy
and laboratories, Al-Kawari was quoted by Kuwait News Agency as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Besides Qatar, the GCC, a regional political and economic
alliance formed in 1981, also comprises Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman,
Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates (UAE). 
