<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Break Up Anti-Nuclear Blockade in Switzerland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Swiss police Wednesday broke up
a two-day protest by Greenpeace activists outside the Gosgen
nuclear power plant, according to the Berne-based European Nuclear
Society.
</P>
<P>
The protesters began the blockade on Tuesday in an attempt to
prevent a train carrying 12 spent fuel elements from leaving the
plant site.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, the European Nuclear Society said that
demonstrators chained themselves to a heavy iron box on a stretch
of railway track, in a bid to stop the transport operation getting
underway today as planned.
</P>
<P>
About 16 members of the local cantonal police force were at the
scene in the early hours of this morning, and six protesters were
arrested and taken away for questioning. The four people in
chains, three men and a woman, remained at the scene overnight,
with police attempting to negotiate a peaceful and voluntary end
to the protest.
</P>
<P>
Police officers cleared the area shortly before noon, and the
train left the site about two hours later as scheduled. The spent
fuel involved is part of a total consignment of 48 elements being
sent to Cogema's reprocessing plant at La Hague in northern
France.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland, France and Germany imposed a ban on such transport
operations in May last year, after contamination on spent fuel
containers became a public issue.
</P>
<P>
France resumed spent fuel transports last year after more
stringent cleaning and monitoring methods were introduced, and the
Swiss authorities recently lifted their ban.
</P>
<P>
The German authorities have not yet given the go-ahead for a
resumption, although preparations for a restart have already been
made by the UK reprocessing firm BNFL. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
