<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fate of Missing S. African Plane Still Unknown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- By Wednesday afternoon
there was still no word on the fate of two pilots who disappeared
over Ethiopia Sunday in a Johannesburg-bound flight, South African
Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Linden Birns, spokesman for aviation group ExecuJet, was quoted
as saying that the pilots, one a South African-based British
national and the other a Swedish citizen, had been equipped with
satellite telephones.
</P>
<P>
"If they had needed to make an unscheduled landing, they would
have contacted us," he said. "We haven't heard a word."
</P>
<P>
Birns said the company was still trying to persuade the
Ethiopian and Eritrean governments to launch a search and rescue
mission for the missing Learjet.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to get them to provide information as to what
may have become of the aircraft," the spokesman said. "We are at
a loss to explain what might have happened."
</P>
<P>
The Learjet 35A, registered in the United States as N350JF, was
piloted by South African-based Alan Lewis, 47, and Swede Anders
Rors, 48.
</P>
<P>
The two freelance pilots were hired to fly the aircraft to
ExecuJet at Lanseria Airport near Johannesburg for refurbishment.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft took off from Luxor in Egypt at 11:25 GMT Sunday
on the second leg of its flight. Eritrean authorities confirmed
that the aircraft entered its airspace at 12:54 GMT.
</P>
<P>
Eritrean air traffic controllers reported losing radio contact
with the plane as it passed about 100 nautical miles southeast of
Eritrean capital Asmara near the Ethiopia-Eritrea border.
</P>
<P>
It was reported on Tuesday that the Ethiopian defense ministry
claimed to have shot down an Eritrean aircraft near Adwa, a north
Ethiopian town not far from Asmara, Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Eritrean authorities subsequently denied that any of its
aircraft had crossed into Ethiopian airspace on that day.
</P>
<P>
Birns said the pilots had submitted flight plans and obtained
the necessary clearance from all the countries whose airspace the
Learjet would cross on its flight to Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea have been at war since May 1998 over the
control of some disputed border areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
