<HEADLINE> Y2K Nearly ironed out in S. African Air Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The South African Air
Traffic and Navigation Services (ATNS) said Wednesday it almost
resolved the Y2K problem and anticipated no air traffic control
chaos in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
ATNS spokesman Peter Marais said navigation, communications and
primary and secondary radar systems were Y2K ready.
</P>
<P>
He said other systems would be tested and upgraded within the
next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
Marais believed there is enough time to retest systems to
identify hitches which might arise after the program was
completed.
</P>
<P>
ATNS is the sole provider of South Africa's air traffic control
services.
</P>
<P>
Y2K is a problem referring to computers' inability to reset
their internal clocks for the year 2000. Without adaption, they
will reset to 1900. 
</P>
</TEXT>
