<HEADLINE> Freed Hostages Arrive in Tehran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Four foreign tourists and
an Iranian freed by their kidnapers after being kept captive for
two weeks arrived in the capital on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
They were abducted from their hotel in the southeastern
province of Kerman on August 14, and released on Tuesday after
intensive negotiations between local security forces and the
kidnapers.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish priest Joaquin Fernandez, 70, and the eldest of the
five, said upon arriving at Tehran's Mehrabad airport: "I am
pleased with my freedom and I think I passed the ordeal."
</P>
<P>
The other freed hostages are Spanish priest Cosme Puerto,
57, Spanish engineer Pedro Garcia, 40, Italian tourist Massimo
Cattabriga, 37, and Iranian guide Rahmatollah Salmani, 33. They
will be reunited with their families soon.
</P>
<P>
The kidnapers belonged to a drug trafficking ring. They took
the five hostages in the hope of exchanging them with two of their
heads jailed by the authorities in recent anti-drug campaign.
</P>
<P>
Newspapers here had reported that the authorities released two
drug traffickers from jail and handed them to the police ready for
the exchange. Local officials had been quoted as saying they tried
every means to ensure the safe return of the hostages, but there
has been no official confirmation about the swap.
</P>
<P>
Cattabriga, the Italian, said he was counting down the moment
to freedom and now he felt at home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
