<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stock Exchange Alliance Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 1 (Xinhua) - Plans to link stock exchanges
across Europe are falling behind schedule, according to British
media reports Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Eight European stock exchanges - led by the London and
Frankfurt stock markets - are in talks to build a single
electronic trading platform for Europe's top stocks, with common
rules and regulations.
</P>
<P>
The London Stock Exchange insists on CrestCo, the UK system,
while Frankfurt wants Deutsche Borse Clearing, its in-house
settlement system, which is merging with Cedel, the pan-European
commercial clearing house.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources said that the issue is far more serious than
outsiders realize. One source close to the talks said: "Clearing
is the key. Anyone can cobble together a deal on the front end.
But if you can have joint settlement and clearing, that is where
the big savings are."
</P>
<P>
"The trouble is both London and Frankfurt have invested a huge
amount of money in their respective systems," the source added.
</P>
<P>
The strains between London and Frankfurt come at a sensitive
time, when the two are set to harmonise their trading hours from
20 september, while others are set to follow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
