<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cost of Health Care Expected to Rise in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The increase in crime and
violence, new diseases and drugs will rocket the cost of health
care and medical aid in the next few years in South Africa,
according to a 1999 health care survey released in Johannesburg
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Health care costs were rising above salary inflation and
medical costs would become more expensive, Old Mutual Health care
managing director Riaan Jordaan said at a media briefing at the
Pharmaceutical Society of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
New diagnostic treatments and the increase in life expectancy
of the ageing population will also contribute to the expected hike
in medical costs, he said.
</P>
<P>
The survey identified cost control and HIV/AIDS as the key
challenges facing the health care system in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Adrian Baskir of Old Mutual health care said HIV/AIDS-related
medical aid benefits accounted for between six and 10 percent
(more than 250 million U.S. dollars) of the total 800 million
dollars spent in the industry on health care costs for 1998.
</P>
<P>
With HIV/AIDS figures soaring, the survey predicted a financial
disaster as the disease would "reduce medical aid scheme reserves
and make health care for all more unaffordable".
</P>
<P>
Jordaan said medical aid fraud was a major problem contributing
to the increase in costs.
</P>
<P>
"If doctors keep seeing family members not subscribed to the
schemes, other members will suffer increases to premiums."
</P>
<P>
Jordaan said managed health care based on the United States
model, which should have provided lower income South Africans with
private health care, proved unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
He said the survey highlighted that managed health care was not
 affordable for low income workers, resulting in accumulated
losses close to 166 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The survey indicated that most medical aid schemes implemented
control over hospital and chronic medicine costs, as well as
forming self-funding benefit plans. However, costs continued to
soar.
</P>
<P>
"Although the initial impact of this was to reduce cost
escalation, health care costs are now starting to outstrip
inflation," Jordaan said.
</P>
<P>
He said this was expected to grow by 40 percent within the next
10 years, costing the country 3.9 billion dollars under managed
care.
</P>
<P>
The survey indicated that most medical schemes had implemented
major managed care programs to control hospital and chronic
medicine costs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
