<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Conservative Leader Attacks Blair on N.Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Britain's main opposition
leader William Hague accused Prime Minister Tony Blair on
Wednesday of betraying the people of Northern Ireland by ruling
that the IRA (Irish Republican Army) ceasefire was still intact.
</P>
<P>
Hague, the Conservative leader, called in an article in the
Daily Telegraph newspaper for an immediate halt to the early
release of guerrilla prisoners under the terms of last year's Good
Friday peace agreement for the British province.
</P>
<P>
He said his Conservative Party wanted to see the Northern
Ireland peace process succeed but all violence had to end.
</P>
<P>
"The Conservative Party is clear about what must now happen.
Paramilitary violence, on both sides, has to end and
decommissioning of illegally held weapons begin," Hague said.
</P>
<P>
"In the meantime, the early release of terrorist prisoners must
immediately be suspended. On any view, it must be unacceptable
that, at a time when IRA terrorism of the most brutal kind
continues, terrorists are being given early release back into
their communities," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hague said Blair's failure on this issue challenged the
sincerity of his pledges and promises to the people of Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
"It is an outrage and a betrayal of the trust of the people of
Northern Ireland," he said.
</P>
<P>
Blair has backed his Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam, who
last week decided that a ceasefire by the Irish Republic Army
(IRA) was still intact despite alleged links to a murder and a
gun-smuggling plot. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
