<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Manufacturing Sector Expands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 1 (Xinhua) - The UK manufacturing sector grew
in August for the third month in a row but began to show tentative
signs of inflation, the Purchasing Managers Index found.
</P>
<P>
The Chartered Institute of Purchasing and Supply said the index
dipped to 52.9 in August from 53.1 in July, signallying expansion
but a slightly slower pace.
</P>
<P>
That growth could fuel fears - fed by Tuesday's reports of
rising house prices - that the UK is returning to boom conditions.
</P>
<P>
The report said the expansion of demand for house and goods led
to an increase in demand for inputs in August, the prices of which
rose for the first time since September 1995.
</P>
<P>
"Input price inflation was further stimulated by the increase in
import prices resulting from the modest depreciation of sterling,"
it added.
</P>
<P>
Economists here believe that it could also heighten
expectations that the Bank of England's Monetary Policy Committee
will move to increase interest rates.
</P>
<P>
An expert at the City said that the index is not in itself
enough to trigger a Bank of England rate hike, but, coming on top
of the nationwide house price index, the Bank will be getting
increasingly twitchy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
