<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fuel Prices Rise in Mocambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican government
Wednesday announced increases in prices for all liquid fuels
except diesel, taking effect immediately.
</P>
<P>
Kerosene rises in price by 10.8 percent, from 2,120 to 2,350
meticais a liter (currently one U.S. dollar equals to 12,800
meticais), according to a press release issued here by the
Ministry of Mineral Reassures and Energy.
</P>
<P>
The price for jet fuel increases by nine percent from 2,555.87
meticais a liter to 2,784.92 meticais.
</P>
<P>
However, Motorists will have to pay only an extra 1.9 percent
for their petrol. A liter of petrol goes up from 6,190 to 6,310
meticais.
</P>
<P>
The price of diesel remains at 4,340 meticais a liter.
</P>
<P>
The largest increase is for cooking gas, which rises by 24.2
percent from 5,651.81 meticais to 7,017.91 meticais per kilo.
</P>
<P>
Since the last alteration in fuel prices on June 1, there had
been a general price increase for petroleum products in the world
market, said the press release.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the Mozambican currency meticai had devalued by
1.1 per cent, it added.
</P>
<P>
This triggered the price changes, which occur whenever the
weighted average price of imported fuels, expressed in meticais,
alters by more than three percent in either direction.
</P>
<P>
The prices indicated for the government are for the main ports
of Maputo, Matola, Beira and Nacala. Fuel distributors elsewhere
are allowed to increase the price to cover their transport costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
