<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-01 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Budget Deficit to Fall By Half: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia's budget
deficit for 1999, which was officially projected at 44 billion
Saudi riyals (11.7 billion U.S. dollars), is likely to fall by
half due to the prospect of growth in state revenues, a Saudi bank
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The total expenditure in the present financial year starting
January 1 is expected at 180 billion riyals (48 billion dollars),
the Saudi-British Bank said in a report, quoted by the Kuwait News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
However, the deficit in the budget is expected to drop to 20
billion riyals (5.3 billion dollars), as the state income is
likely to reach 160 billion riyals (42.66 billion dollars) by
year-end, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The fresh forecast put the oil revenues at 110 billion riyals
(29.33 billion dollars) and non-oil income at 50 billion riyals
(13.33 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The kingdom's 1999 budget, which was unveiled last December,
projected the expenditure at 165 billion riyals (44 billion
dollars) and total revenues at 121 billion riyals (32.3 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, the world's dominant oil power, has been running
high budget deficits in the past two years as the country was hit
hard by the sagging oil prices in global oil markets.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 budget carried a deficit of 17 billion riyals (4.5
billion dollars) while the budget deficit for the 1998 financial
year was 18 billion riyals (4.8 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Oil prices, however, rebounded dramatically since April 1,
when member states of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC) and non-OPEC producers began to cut their output.
</P>
<P>
World benchmark Brent crude futures for October delivery on
Tuesday hit a 22-month high of 21.3 dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, world leading oil producers, including Saudi Arabia,
have urged OPEC and non-OPEC nations to keep in place their
current production cuts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
