<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDB Approves Grant for Brazilian Renewable Energy Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American
Development Bank (IDB) announced Wednesday the approval of a grant
of 898,950 U.S. dollars to support a Brazilian program that
promotes decentralized energy services based on renewable sources
in isolated communities.
</P>
<P>
The resources from the Japan Special Fund, which is
administered by the Washington-based IDB, will help the Brazilian
government improve the management and the effectiveness of its
program, known as PRODEEM, for developing renewable energy
services in rural municipalities.
</P>
<P>
The project will create a framework designed to attract
investment to renewable energy systems and renewable energy-based
services that can improve the quality of life and raise
productivity in isolated populations that lack access to modern
and clean sources of energy.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, PRODEEM would step up the transfer of
project execution to decentralized market agents and the private
sector. It would also provide training to the agents and assist
small and medium size enterprises in using renewable energy to
boost their productive capacity.
</P>
<P>
The project also seeks to reduce deforestation due to the use
of wood and charcoal as energy sources as well as to decrease
missions from poorly maintained diesel generators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Denies Seeking Delay in IMF Loan to Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The United States Wednesday
denied that it seeks a halt in the loan from the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) to Russia.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the U.S. newspaper USA Today published
Wednesday, Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said the United
States will seek a pause in the aid from the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) to Russia until there is an adequate
safeguards for the money.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. will not support disbursement of the next tranche
without adequate safeguards to assure that any funds disbursed are
used properly (and) without adequate accounting," Summers told the
newspaper Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, a spokeswoman for the Treasury Department said what
Summers said did not mean that the U.S. seeks a delay to
disbursements from the IMF's latest lending program to Russia.
</P>
<P>
"As it normally does, the IMF is doing its review with respect
to the second tranche and it would be premature to make any
judgement as to whether Russia will meet the conditions for that
disbursement," the spokeswoman told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"The United States has insisted that there be adequate
safeguards in place with respect to the current program and that
there be an adequate accounting for the use of past funds," she
said.
</P>
<P>
The 182-member IMF is scheduled to release another 640 million
U.S. dollars of a 4.5 billion U.S. dollars loan package to Russia.
USA Today said the IMF has lent Russia 20 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that some of the 10 billion U.S. dollars allegedly
funneled through the Bank of New York by Russian gangsters in a
money-laundering scheme may have involved IMF loans to Russia.
</P>
<P>
The British Pricewaterhouse auditing firm has been conducting a
study on the IMF loans. The U.S. government is also investigating
the allegations. But an IMF official said Monday that there was no
evidence that the IMF loans were misused.
</P>
<P>
"As these investigations continue and as these revelations come
to light, we'll have to make judgements about what constitutes a
satisfactory accounting," Summers was quoted by USA Today as
saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
