<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Deplores Attacks on Civilians in Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) deplored Saturday's "brutal raids in
Burundi" which resulted in the death of dozens of people,
including children, the U.N. agency said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The raid follows months of similar violence in which the
victims have included innocent children," a UNICEF statement said.
"It is intolerable that children be the victims of senseless and
wanton bloodshed by any side in the conflict."
</P>
<P>
"Saturday's raid occurred four days after the United Nations
Security Council adopted a resolution on children in armed
conflict which condemned the targeting of children, including
killing, maiming, sexual violence and recruitment of young people
as soldiers," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The tragedy in Burundi is a clear call to the international
community that it must now act forcefully to protect the rights of
children, not only in Burundi but in all other theaters of armed
conflict," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations aimed at ending the nearly six-year-old impasse
in Burundi were scheduled to resume in Dar Es Salaam, capital of
Tanzania, in early September.
</P>
<P>
"With further violence threatened, UNICEF urges all parties
to come to the negotiating table and to give special attention
to the protection of children in such conflicts," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Hutu rebels attacked the capital in brutal overnight
raids, murdering 38 civilians and taking on the army in fierce
fighting that killed another 20 people, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Burundi has been locked in a series of ethnic conflicts between
the Hutu majority and Tutsi minority over the past three decades.
About 150,000 people, most of them civilians, have been killed
since civil war again erupted in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
