<HEADLINE> U.N. to Deploy Team to Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations will
send a three-person team out Thursday from the U.N. Headquarters
in New York to Congo (K) to pave the way for the deployment of the
first phase of U.N. military personnel to Congo (K) and other
concerned countries in the region, a U.N. spokesman said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The team, composed of staff of the Department of Peacekeeping
Operations, is leaving Thursday evening, Fred Eckhard, the U.N.
spokesman, said, adding that it will travel to Nairobi, where it
is expected to assemble within a week the initial group of United
Nations military liaison officers.
</P>
<P>
Four members of the team will support the Joint Military
Committee to be established in Lusaka, Zambia, while six members
will set up an advance United Nations headquarters in Kinshasa,
Congo (K), he said.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 16 members will be dispatched to regional
capitals of the signatories of the ceasefire accord, initially
Bunumbura, Kigali, Kinshasa, Kampala, Windhock and Harare.
</P>
<P>
The dispatch was made in the wake of the rebels signing of the
Lusaka ceasefire accord for Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
The dispatch of these officers is the first phase of a
three-stage plan outlined by the secretary-general in his July 15
report to the Security Council on the Democratic Republic of
Congo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
