<HEADLINE> U.S. Leading Economic Indicators Rise In July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Composite Index of
Leading Economic Indicators in the United States rose 0.3
percent in July, the same pace as in the prior two months, the
Conference Board, the U.S. prominent research group, said in a
report Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
With the increase of 0.3 percent in July, the leading
index stands at 108.0, the report said. This Index has
registered increases in nine of the last ten months.
</P>
<P>
"Seven of the 10 leading indicators posted increases,
underscoring the continuing strength of the current economic
expansion," said ken Goldstein, Conference Board Economist. "The
two key drivers of this latest increase were manufacturing and
the labor market."
</P>
<P>
Goldstein said "There are concerns that the two interest-rate
hikes this Summer could slow growth later this year. Indeed, the
financial indicators were the weakest component of the index."
</P>
<P>
"But overall, strength in manufacturing conditions and a
robust labor market more than offset the negative contribution
of higher interest rates," he said.
</P>
<P>
The leading indicators are calculated from a base of 100,
set in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
