<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Community Criticized on African Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa said Wednesday that the international community is
not paying sufficient attention to the problem of refugees in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said it is hard to understand why a refugee in Europe,
like those from Kosovo, is getting assistance that is almost 10
times what a refugee in Africa is gaining.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian President made the remarks in Sweden while
delivering a speech at a lecture on "Peace-Making and Conflicts
Resolution in Africa" at the Aula Magna University of Uppsala,
reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
With such little support, he said, Africa feels difficult to
solve the problem that is not only a product of conflicts but also
one of the factors causing a vicious cycle of conflicts.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that no continent like Africa is currently
embroiled in so many armed conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Africa is hosting 7.1 million or 34 percent of 21.1 million
refugees in the world and that Tanzania alone is currently hosting
at least 890,000 refugees.
</P>
<P>
"This is an enormous burden on a poor country like Tanzania in
economic, social, political and environmental terms," he said,
adding that his country has never refused the entry of any
refugee.
</P>
<P>
"We take them in a humanitarian gesture and as an international
 obligation," he said.
</P>
<P>
The former colonial powers and those who turned Africa into
the battlefield of east and west during the Cold War, must be held
responsible for a number of African conflicts and should
contribute actively to finding a solution to the conflicts, Mkapa
stressed.
</P>
<P>
He said colonialism and the Cold War turned upside down the
Africans' way of life that had an in-built mechanism for
preventing and resolving conflicts and building social cohesion
within participatory democracy.
</P>
<P>
"Until this day Africa is yet to recapture its pre-colonial
traditions and ways of life," he said, adding that state
repression, a colonial legacy, and politics of exclusion and
bigotry continue to trigger armed insurgencies.
</P>
<P>
He mentioned other contributing factors to the African
conflicts as poverty and under development.
</P>
<P>
"Unquestionably the solution to African conflicts is also the
responsibility of the international community," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Mkapa said regional economic integration as a good way
of reducing potential or risk of conflicts and expansionism.
</P>
<P>
The president said there is also a growing consensus that
African countries should concentrate on preventing conflicts,
something that could be achieved through several ways including
giving more attention to nation building and civic education to
inculcate the sense of nationhood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0072 </DOCNO>
