<HEADLINE> European Main Stock Markets End In Black </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- European main stock markets
ended in black as a rebound by U.S. shares and a stronger euro
tempered anxiety about rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 finished 29.8 points or 0.48 percent higher
at 6,276.2, partially recovering from a 2 percent sell-off in the
previous session.
</P>
<P>
Oil producer BP Amoco advanced 1.65 percent to 1,166 pence,
while rival Shell Transport added 2.17 percent to 506 pence,
supported by a recent rise in crude oil prices.
</P>
<P>
British Aerospace rose 2.15 percent after applying for an 800
million U.S. dollars loan to support its share of the development
cost of Airbus Industrie's Planned 600 seat super jumbo aircraft.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts said the market's nerves remained shaky and
the FTSE was likely to drift ahead of key U.S. labor data Friday
as worries over the outlook for U.S. interest rates continued to
haunt investors.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, the electronic Xetra Dax closed up 0.88 percent,
or 46.35 points, at 5,317.12, boosted by a confident start on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
The spotlight was centered on the utility and financial
sectors. Viag soared 7.96 percent after it was confirmed Tuesday
that the group was in merger talks with rival Veba, which climbed
4.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Paris' CAC 40 closed up 0.96 percent at 4,633.38, near its
session high of 4,634.03, after a modest rally underpinned by
strength in oil and auto stocks. 
</P>
