<HEADLINE> Moscoso Assumes Presidency of Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The 54-year-old Mireya
Moscoso was sworn in as the new president of Panama Wednesday,
becoming the first female president of the country.
</P>
<P>
In front of around 25,000 viewers in the National Stadium,
among whom some 40 special guests came from other countries,
Moscoso pledged to respect the Constitution and fight against the
poverty which affects thousands of Panamanians.
</P>
<P>
Moscoso took over a country in a better shape financially than
its Central American neighbors to the north and Colombia to the
south.
</P>
<P>
Panama with less than 3 million people has had a 4 percent
economic growth this year. The country's development is backed up
by 2 billion U.S. dollars in foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
The Latin American country gets more than 500 million dollars
in tolls every year from the famous Panama Canal.
</P>
<P>
However, President Moscoso will have a difficult time
supervising the handing over of the Inter-Oceanic Canal to Panama
at the end of this year, in addition to fighting the poverty which
is an everyday part of life in Panama. 
</P>
