<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Urges Peace in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council on Wednesday condemned the violence in East Timor after a
ballot on its future on Monday, while holding Indonesia
responsible for the peace and security during vote-counting.
</P>
<P>
It underlined the need for non-violence in the post-ballot
period and demanded the arrest of rioters and immediate steps by
Indonesia to prevent new incidents from occurring.
</P>
<P>
The statement was made by September council president, the
Netherlands' Arnold Peter van Walsum following a closed-door
council meeting.
</P>
<P>
A similar statement was made by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan.
</P>
<P>
At least two people were reportedly killed in Dili, capital of
East Timor on Wednesday, U.N. sources said.
</P>
<P>
The incident took place nearby the compound of the United
Nations Mission in East Timor (UNAMET) with local militia members
involved.
</P>
<P>
However, vote-counting continued undisturbed during the
incident, said U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary figures show that 98.6 percent of some 450,000
eligible voters cast their ballots.
</P>
<P>
All boxes arrived in Dili on Tuesday and the process of
so-called ballot reconciliation began Wednesday morning, Eckhard
said.
</P>
<P>
The two-day reconciliation would see if the number of ballots
cast is matched with the number of people who voted.
</P>
<P>
On Friday and Saturday actual counting of ballots will be done,
Eckhard added.
</P>
<P>
Replying to a question on the possibility of establishing a
peacekeeping force for East Timor, the spokesman ruled out such an
arrangement, saying that Indonesia is fully responsible for the
security in the territory according to the May 5 agreement.
</P>
<P>
The accord signed by Foreign Ministers of Indonesia and
Portugal and the U.N. Secretary-General paved the way for the
ballot to determine the status of East Timor -- part of Indonesia
with special autonomy or independence.
</P>
<P>
In the past 23 years, clashes between pro and anti-independence
parties have featured the political scene in East Timor, a
Portuguese colony until 1975 when Indonesia occupied it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Denies Seeking Delay in IMF Loan to Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The United States on
Wednesday denied that it seeks a halt in the loan from the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) to Russia.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the U.S. newspaper USA today published
Wednesday, Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said the United
States will seek a pause in the aid from the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) to Russia until there is an adequate
safeguards for the money.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. will not support disbursement of the next tranche
without adequate safeguards to assure that any funds disbursed are
used properly (and) without adequate accounting," Summers told the
newspaper on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, a spokeswoman for the Treasury Department said what
Summers said did not mean that the U.S. seeks a delay to
disbursements from the IMF's latest lending program to Russia.
</P>
<P>
"As it normally does, the IMF is doing its review with respect
to the second tranche and it would be premature to make any
judgement as to whether Russia will meet the conditions for that
disbursement," the spokeswoman told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"The United States has insisted that there be adequate
safeguards in place with respect to the current program and that
there be an adequate accounting for the use of past funds," she
said.
</P>
<P>
In an telephone interview with Xinhua, a Treasury spokesman
said everything Summers said had been correctly quoted in USA
Today except the title of the story -- "U.S. Seeks Pause in
Russian Loans."
</P>
<P>
The 182-member IMF is scheduled to release another 640 million
U.S. dollars of a 4.5 billion U.S. dollars loan package to Russia.
USA Today said the IMF has lent Russia 20 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that some of the 10 billion U.S. dollars allegedly
funneled through the Bank of New York by Russian gangsters in a
money-laundering scheme may have involved IMF loans to Russia.
</P>
<P>
The money laundering and corruption charges are "serious," said
State Department spokesman Phil Reeker at a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
"The investigation is ongoing, and facts in that case are still
being established," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously we will not provide assistance to Russia unless we
can be sure it will support market and other reforms in that
country and will not be misused or diverted. The IMF, the World
Bank and other international financial institutions take a similar
approach," he added.
</P>
<P>
But Reeker noted that many reports in the U.S. media are just
speculation, which are "outdated or perhaps factually incorrect."
</P>
<P>
The British Pricewaterhouse auditing firm has been conducting a
study on the IMF loans. The U.S. administration is also
investigating the allegations. But an IMF official said on Monday
that there was no evidence that the IMF loans were misused.
</P>
<P>
"As these investigations continue and as these revelations come
to light, we'll have to make judgements about what constitutes a
satisfactory accounting," Summers was quoted by USA today as
saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
