<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Debt-to-Equity Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Cinda Assets Management Corp.
signed an agreement with the Beijing Building Materials Group
today on the debt-to-equity transfer of the Beijing Cement Plant,
the first deal of its kind in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Cement Plant, a subsidiary of Beijing Building
Materials Group, will reduce its asset liability ratio from 80.1
percent to 32.4 percent after the deal, which is hoped to bring an
annual profit of more than 20 million yuan (2.4 million U.S.
dollars) beginning in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The plant will also be transformed into a limited liability
company with both Cinder and the Beijing Building Materials Group
as its shareholders.
</P>
<P>
With a daily output of 2,000 tons of cement, the Beijing Cement
Plant is one of the major state-owned enterprises in China. By the
end of 1998, the plant's total debt had amounted to 968 million
yuan, which plunged it into chaos.
</P>
<P>
China has resorted to debt-to-equity conversions in tackling
floundering large and medium-sized state enterprises in a move to
pull them out of difficulty in three years.
</P>
<P>
The Cinda Assets Management Corp., established in March, mainly
focuses on writing off bad loans from commercial banks to push
forward the reform of state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
China is setting up a number of asset-management companies to
take over the non-performing loans of its commercial banks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
