<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Flight Ban Has Negative Impacts on Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The decision on banning all
flights to and from Somalia by the Kenyan government has already
shown its impacts in Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Nine local airlines offices were closed Thursday, of which
three had been taking passengers to and from Kenya while six
others had been working on the khat business.
</P>
<P>
The agencies in charge of the passenger planes are the first to
close down their business, while those of the khat are still
struggling to survive.
</P>
<P>
The passengers planning to leave for Kenya have been
disappointed, but some of them have already resorted to using the
route via terra to Nairobi sneaking through the already closed
borderlines between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The ban will also bring bankruptcy to the local travel agencies
open in almost all of the main towns in Somalia including Kismayu,
Mogadishu, Beletuein, Galkaio, Bossaso and others.
</P>
<P>
However, the main khat business dealers said they are not
getting stuck by the Kenyan ban, but will simply turn to Ethiopia
for importing the widely chewed narcotic leaves of khat.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan khat is known as Mirow, while the stuff from
Ethiopia is called Hareri. The Hareri is consumed in northern
Somalia while the Mirow is used in the south.
</P>
<P>
On the positive side of the flight ban, the absence of the khat
from Mogadishu's markets has also affected the souring rate
between the Somali shilling and the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Somali shilling has dramatically been devaluating ever
since the illegal huge consignments of the Somali bank notes were
imported by the local businessmen earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
The dollar lost its value considerably Thursday with one dollar
 equalling only 9,900 shillings. Before the ban, only a week ago,
one dollar was equal to 10,150 shillings.
</P>
<P>
The businessmen in the main business center of Bakara market
attributed the sharp fall of the dollar value to its shrinking
demands in the exchange wards of the market following the ban
imposed on all flights to and from Somalia by Kenyan President
Daniel Arap Moi.
</P>
<P>
The khat dealers are believed to have been using more than
300,000 dollars everyday for the importation of the khat from
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Some of the businessmen also said the recent United Nations
report on Somalia and its proposed meeting on Somalia by the U.N.
Security Council has lowered the value of the dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
