<HEADLINE> Only One  S. African  to Join U.N. Force in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Only one South African
will be among the first group of U.N. military liaison officers to
be deployed in the Congo to supervise the implementation of the
cease-fire accord, Defense Minister Patrick Lekota said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
South Africa had said it was prepared to contribute eight
officers to the 30-member group, but the U.N. had asked for only
one, South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted Lekota as
saying in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
The year-long fighting in the Democratic Republic of the Congo
was officially over when all founding members of the major rebel
group, the Congolese Rally for Democracy, signed the cease-fire
agreement in Lusaka on Tuesday, which had been signed in July by
six countries involved in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. group would probably assemble in Kenya for
pre-deployment training before going to the Congo, but the date of
their deployment was not yet known, according to SAPA.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is willing to comply with any U.N. requests for
assistance in the Congo mission, and further training of personnel
is underway. 
</P>
