<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New WTO Chief Outlines Priorities for Third Ministerial Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The New Director-General of the
World Trade Organization (WTO) Mike Moore has underscored his
priorities for the upcoming ministerial conference in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
During his first press conference since assuming his post on
September 1, Moore, the first non-European to head the WTO,
stressed the importance of achieving a balanced outcome in the
Seattle conference which will address the needs of all WTO members.
</P>
<P>
"Seattle is the priority, but the Seattle Ministerial will only
be judged a success if there is a balanced outcome," Moore said on
Thursday. "We need to assist all member governments to engage in
the process. Thus we need to increase the levels and focus of
technical assistance from the WTO and other sources to make this
happen."
</P>
<P>
The priorities spelled out by the WTO's new chief include:
facilitating and assisting countries to achieve a balanced outcome
from the negotiations, which will benefit the more vulnerable
economies; advocating the advantages -- for the great nations and
the more modest nations -- of a more open trading system and how
that can increase living standards and build a more prosperous,
safer world; strengthening the WTO and its system and rules, to
build on and maintain its reputation for integrity and fairness,
and to re-shape the organization to reflect the new reality of its
membership and their needs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
