<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10 U.S.Tourists Found Dead in Plane Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 2 (Xinhua) -- All 12 people including
10 U.S. tourists boarding a plane that crashed in Tanzania's
northern Arusha Region have been found dead, Regional Commissioner
Daniel Njoolay told Xinhua Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"They are dead. The bodies are in pieces," Njoolay said over
telephone from Arusha.
</P>
<P>
He said that the tragedy was reported by policemen who have
arrived at the scene, which lies in a forest on the slope of a
hill, but he said there is no fire burning.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian policemen and U.S. rescuers are still at the scene
investigating the incident, he said.
</P>
<P>
Dudley Sims, Director of United States Information Services in
Dar es Salaam, confirmed the deaths.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether there are any survivors, the U.S. official said:
"I don't think so."
</P>
<P>
He declined to comment how long U.S. rescuers will stay at the
scene, nor would he say whether the black box has been found or
not.
</P>
<P>
The small charter plane, which crashed Wednesday morning, was
carrying six male and four female U.S. tourists from the
world-famous Serengeti National Park to the Kilimanjaro Airport in
northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
On board the Cessna 404 aircraft, which went down some 12 miles
away from the 14,979-foot Mount Meru, the fifth highest in Africa,
were also a Tanzanian tour guide and a pilot whose nationality is
not known.
</P>
<P>
Mount Meru, often surrounded by cloud, is a part of the Arusha
National Park located some 45 kilometers from the Arusha town in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Acting Permanent Secretary in the Ministry of Natural Resources
and Tourism, R.P. Kabende, left here Thursday morning for Arusha
to handle issues related to the incident.
</P>
<P>
The tourists included three couples and a group of four that
came from Florida, Massachusetts, Connecticut, California and New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the crash is still under investigation, the
police said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
