<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. New Jobless Claims Increase Last Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September (Xinhua) -- The Labor Department said the
number of new claims for unemployment benefits edged up last week.
</P>
<P>
There were 289,000 people who filed new claims for jobless
benefits for the week ending August 28, up by 4,000 from the
previous week, the Department reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The four-week average for claims was up to 286,500 last week.
It was the highest level since Aug. 7, when claims were at 288,250.
</P>
<P>
Last week's rise in new claims was in line with many economists
' expectations. Economists consider jobless claims levels below
300,000 an indication of an extremely tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
The Department said that for the week ending August 21, 14
states and territories reported increases in new jobless claims
while 39 reported decreases. The state data lags a week behind the
national figures.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the state with the biggest increase in
applications for jobless benefits was Georgia, up 1,538, while the
state with the biggest decrease in jobless benefits claims was
Michigan, down 1,642. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
