<HEADLINE> Chinese Taipei Upset Japan to Enter Top-four </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUKUOKA, Japan, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Taipei
upset host Japan 77-68 by a 1-2 punch of Lo Shin-liang and Cheng
Chih-lung in the final minute of a quarterfinal round match at the
Asian Men's Basketball Championship here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Guard Lo scored a team-high 25 points and Cheng added 24 to
storm Chinese Taipei, who lost to Japan twice in the past two
versions of the Asian championship, into the semi-final against
tournament favorite China, who trounced Lebanon 107-67 earlier
this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Reigning champions South Korea wrapped up their quarter-finals
with the third win after defeating Syria 70-62, setting up a meet
with Saudi Arabia, who ousted Kuwait 93-80 in a physical match.
</P>
<P>
The semi-finalists will take one day off the schedule with
teams in the classification playoffs competing for placing from
the 5th to the 12th on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Even the 2.06-meter Weiss Dan tried to threw 3-pointers when
Chinese Taipei, who lost to South Korea on Monday and finished
second in group F after the win, led by as much as seven points
from a 9-0 run with 1:18 to go on the clock.
</P>
<P>
Japan's top scorer Orimo Takehiko, who scored 16 points, had
two 3-pointers down the stretch to close the game, but his
outrange efforts were cut off by deadly foul free-throws of the
Chinese Taipei, which was 15-27 on the line.
</P>
<P>
"We made mistakes down the stretch, and we paid the price,"
said Dan, who made 3-pointers attempts when his teammates could
not get into the solid defense of the Chinese Taipei.
</P>
<P>
Lo made a game-winning three-pointer to extend Chinese Taipei's
lead to 69-62 from Chou Chun-San's assist with 2:14 left remaining.
</P>
<P>
"I had nothing in my mind but to make the basket at that time,
" Lo talked about his best shot of the game.
</P>
<P>
"The Japanese had more pressure than us to make into the semi
because they are the hosts," said Chen, who was ABC Most All-Round
Player in Asia last year.
</P>
<P>
China won its fifth-consecutive game in the tournament, which
started on August 28, with no player was given more than 20
minutes on the court by head coach Jiang Xingquan.
</P>
<P>
"I want to have more players ready for the semi-final and final
game," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Sun Jun led the squad with 17 points with China shot 10-28 from
behind the arch and 34-52 in the field.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong of China squandered a 11-point lead in the first half
to lose to Bahrain 93-70 in the classification round, while the
United Arab Emirates beat Malaysia 88-75.
</P>
<P>
The UAE will face Uzbekistan, who routed Thailand 83-71, on
Friday's 9-10 placing playoffs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
