<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Champion Zhan Xugang Sets New World Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN,CHINA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Spurred on by the strong
rival from Iran while cheered on by the enthusiastic local fans,
Atlanta Olympic champion Zhan Xugang from China broke the clean
and jerk world record in the men's 77kg category at the Asian
Weightlifting Championships here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 25-year-old Zhan jerked 206.0 kilograms at his third
attempt,surpassing the previous mark 205.5kg set by Aranda
Idalberto of Cuba at the Pan America Games in Winnipeg, Canada on
August 5.
</P>
<P>
"I had never expect to break the world record at this
championships. I am very blessed," said Zhan, who swept three
world records for the total champion in the 70kg division at the
Atlanta Olympic Games in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Hosscin from Iran changed the weight twice for his
final attempt before he failed to jerk 202.5kg which spurred
emulative Zhan to challenge the world record.
</P>
<P>
Zhan won the total champion for 365.0kg while his compatriot Li
Hongli claimed the victory in the snatch with 160.0kg, edging Zhan
to the second place on the same bar for his lighter body weight.
</P>
<P>
Li won the silver medal for a total of 350.0kg and Hosscin took
the bronze medals in the snatch and total with 155.0 and 345.0kg,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
"We were 60 percent certain that Zhan would break the jerk
world record before tonight's competition, and he did it," said
the excited national head coach Yang Hanxiong.
</P>
<P>
Chinese strongwoman Xu Xuefen swept three gold medals in the
women's 63kg class for a winning total 215kg, followed by Yoon I-
Sook of South Korea 202.5kg and Nansita Devi of India 185.0kg.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Israeli Sources Say Pact to be Signed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak and Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat
will apparently sign a revised Wye agreement in Alexandria, Egypt
on Friday morning, senior Israeli sources said.
</P>
<P>
The sources were quoted by Israel Radio as saying that
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, Jordan's King Abdullah and
United States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will take part
in the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The positive comments came after the talks between Israeli and
Palestinian negotiators hit a snag as both sides refused to
compromise on the prisoner issue Thursday.
</P>
<P>
As part of a revised Wye accord, Israel offered to release 356
Palestinians held for anti-Israeli activities, while the
Palestinians sought the release of 400.
</P>
<P>
Israel has said principles were at stake and that it would not
release Palestinians who killed Israelis.
</P>
<P>
But senior Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat accused Israel
of "escalating the situation at the final moment for no reason."
</P>
<P>
"We reject this way of dealing with us," Erekat added.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators have intensified efforts in
the last few days to bridge their gaps over the implementation of
the Wye accord, signed and then frozen by Barak's hard-line
predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu late last year.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have virtually been on the verge of an
agreement. In the previous talks, they have made significant
progress on most issues concerning the implementation of the Wye
accord, including a timetable of further Israeli troop withdrawals
from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Wye agreement calls on Israel to hand over 13 percent of
the West Bank to the Palestinians in three stages over a period of
12 weeks and release hundreds of Palestinian prisoners. Netanyahu
froze the deal after carrying out its first stage.
</P>
<P>
Ousting Netanyahu in the national elections three months ago
on a platform to revive the Middle East peace process on all
tracks, Barak has promised to carry out the Wye agreement but
proposed some changes in its implementation.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have accepted his proposal to divide the two
remaining phases of Israeli troop withdrawals into three stages
and put off the final stage until early next year to avoid
potential confrontation between Palestinians and Jewish settlers.
</P>
<P>
They have also agreed upon several sideline issues such as the
construction of a seaport in Gaza and the opening of safe passages
between Gaza and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israel has said that if the two sides could not agree on all
issues, it would carry out the Wye agreement as written, meaning
all understandings recently reached including those on the
seaport and safe passages would not be implemented. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Displays Archives on Ceremony of Founding of New China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 2 (Xinhua)-- A complete set of archives
related to the ceremony of the founding of New China on October 1,
1949, has been open to visitors at the China No. 2 Historical
Archives at Nanjing, capital of East China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
The files contain slogans used at the ceremony, designs for
badges, invitation cards, a list of guards, the temporary
telephone number for the Tiananmen Rostrum, as well as
applications for a budget increase.
</P>
<P>
Guo Biqiang, a museum official, said that the files contain
over 20 items, most of which are hand-written by the senior
leaders in pen or pencil on rough paper. The rough items are
indicative of the harsh economic conditions at the time when the
People's Republic was founded.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
