<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Thirds of CIS States Post Industrial Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 2 (Xinhua) -- In the first seven months of
the year, industrial growth occurred in eight of the twelve member
countries of the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS), the
Russian Statistics Agency said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Citing figures from the CIS Interstate Statistics Committee,
the agency said the greatest industrial growth occurred in
Tajikistan with 6.6 percent, Belarus with 6.5 percent, Armenia
with 5.7 percent and Uzbekistan, with 5.6 percent
</P>
<P>
Industrial production went up in Russia by 4.5 percent, in
Azerbaijan by 2.7 percent, in Georgia by 0.4 percent, and in
Ukraine by 0.3 percent. The CIS Statistics Committee has no
information for Turkmenistan, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The greatest increase in gross domestic product (GDP) in the
first seven months of 1999, as compared with the same period last
year, was achieved by Azerbaijan with 6 percent and Armenia with 5.
4 percent.
</P>
<P>
In Kyrgyzstan, the GDP increased by 3.7 percent, in Tajikistan
by 2.1 percent, in Belarus by 1.0 percent. In Ukraine, the GDP
dropped 2.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to preliminary figures, the GDP went down by 3.3
percent in Kazakhstan and by 1 percent in Russia in the first half
of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The CIS Statistics Committee said that during the first seven
months of the year, the highest rate of inflation was observed in
Belarus at 97.2 percent. In Kyrgyzstan, consumer prices went up by
32.5 percent, in Russia by 28 percent, in Moldova by 25.6 percent
and in Tajikistan, 23.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
In Armenia, inflation stood at 0.9 percent from January to
July, in Kazakhstan, 12.9 percent, in Ukraine, 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, consumer prices went down by 2.4 percent in
Azerbaijan. There is no corresponding information for Georgia,
Turkmenistan or Uzbekistan, Interfax said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
