<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teen-Ager Adimts to Killing Acquaintance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 2 (Xinhua) -- As part of a plea bargain, a
teen-ager pleaded guilty in Tel Aviv District Court on Thursday to
the 1997 murder of an acquaintance in the United States.
</P>
<P>
In return, Samuel Sheinbein, 19, would be sentenced to 24 years
in an Israeli prison.
</P>
<P>
The judge convicted Sheinbein, from Maryland, the U.S., of
premeditated murder minutes after he admitted to the murder. But
the judge did not rule immediately whether he would approve the
bargain deal.
</P>
<P>
Sheinbein fled to Israel shortly after his acquaintance Alfred
Tello's body was found burned and dismembered in an garage near
his home in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
Althogh Sheinbein grew up in the U.S., he claimed Israeli
citizenship because his father was born here in 1944, and said he
could not be extradited under an Israeli law prohibiting
extradition of Israeli citizens to face trial abroad.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Supreme Court has uphold Sheinbein's claim.
</P>
<P>
Under Israeli law, which is more lenient than that of the
U.S., Sheinbein could be paroled after 16 years.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors from Maryland said the penalty was too much light.
</P>
<P>
But Israel's attorney general, who had worked out the plea
bargain, defended it on grounds that a 24-year sentence is the
heaviest which can be imposed in Israel on a minor. At the time
of murder, Sheinbein was 17 years old. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
