<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea, Russia to Seek Closer Military Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Russian Defense
Minister Igor Sergeyev and his South Korean counterpart Cho Sung-
tae agreed to strengthen military cooperation and expand military
exchanges for the sake of security and stability on the Korean
peninsula and in northeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
During nearly two hours of closed-door talks on Thursday, the
two ministers signed a memorandum of understanding calling for
increased military exchanges and cooperation in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum calls for exchanges of visits by the two
countries' top military leaders, navy port calls and jointly
conducting search-and-rescue sea exercises for peaceful aims.
</P>
<P>
The two military chiefs also agreed to sign an agreement on the
prevention of dangerous military operations between South Korea
and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev arrived in Seoul on a three-day visit, during which
time he is scheduled to meet President Kim Dae-jung and visit some
South Korean military facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
