<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Sign Agriculture Protocol With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government's
food security program will shift to high gear with the signing
later this month of a protocol with China to strengthen
cooperation between the two countries in agriculture and
fisheries.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Edgardo Angara of the Department of Agriculture is
set to leave for China to officially sign the document aimed at
strengthening agricultural productivity while improving the
standards of living of people in both countries.
</P>
<P>
Angara said Thursday that his scheduled visit to China next
week highlights the importance of agriculture in the national
development of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on agricultural cooperation was first reached
during Chinese Agriculture Minister Chen Yaobang's visit to
Manila in July when the two countries signed a declaration of
intent to enter into a protocol on cooperation in agriculture and
fisheries.
</P>
<P>
During Chen's Manila visit, he and Angara conducted extensive
and in-depth discussions on agricultural issues, especially
technological assistance to be provided by China in forms of farm
machinery and the use of high-yielding rice seeds.
</P>
<P>
"The Philippines will learn so much from China, which has
succeeded in providing sufficient food for its 1.2 billion people
despite the constraints that it has to contend with," Angara said.
</P>
<P>
He added that he is also proposing a joint venture with China
on the development of lower-cost high-yielding seeds, which China
has successfully developed.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Philippine President Joseph Estrada has sent a
government team to China to study agricultural technology and
explore ways to improve the country's agriculture sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
