<HEADLINE> Moore Supports China's Bid to Enter WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- China, as an economic power, is
entitled to membership in the World Trade Organization (WTO), said
the organization's new chief here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Everybody, every member in the WTO, wants China to sit at the
table (at the third ministerial conference in Seattle later this
year) as it should," Director-General Mike Moore told Xinhua at
his first press conference after taking office at the Geneva-based
WTO.
</P>
<P>
"China ought to be a member of the WTO," said the former New
Zealand prime minister. "And it will be a splendid thing when that
's achieved."
</P>
<P>
"It is a very good thing that presidents of China and the
United States will be meeting in Auckland," he added. He believes
the meeting will promote negotiations on China's entry into the
world trade body.
</P>
<P>
On China's accession to the WTO, Moore said, "from my point of
view, I think it would be a great thing and a splendid thing that
would make all of us proud."
</P>
<P>
At the same time, he noted, the WTO is managed by its members,
and it is the members who decide on the acceptance of new members.
</P>
<P>
But Moore pledged that he and his organization would do
everything possible to help create conditions for China's early
entry into the WTO; he encouraged WTO members to make new efforts
toward that end. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Refuses to Host Rwanda Genocide Convicts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has rejected a U.N.
proposal to host the 1994 Rwanda genocide convicts, Times of
Zambia reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Home Affairs Minister Peter Machungwa as
confirming in parliament Wednesday that "after weighing all pros
and cons, Zambia has decided that it will not host Rwandan
genocide prisoners and having made that decision we have already
informed the International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) in
Arusha about the move."
</P>
<P>
He did not disclose the reason for the refusal.
</P>
<P>
Last month the ICTR offered financial assistance to Zambia to
rehabilitate some prisons it had inspected to keep the convicts.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR earlier in the year requested the Zambian government
to host the 1994 genocide suspects after convictions.
</P>
<P>
The release of the funds was subject to the government's
willingness to host the convicts.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR was set up by the U.N. to try those implicated in the
1994 genocide in which Hutu extremists killed over 500,000 Tutsis
and moderate Hutus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
