<HEADLINE> Manila Creates Cabinet Task Force on Charter Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada ordered Thursday the creation of the Cabinet Task Force on
Constitutional Correction for Development (Concord).
</P>
<P>
Presidential spokesman Jerry Barican said the aim of the task
force is to oversee the government's communication plan and
information campaign on the proposed amendments to the 1987
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the creation of the Cabinet Task Force was
based on the recommendation of the participants in the Cabinet
Workshop on constitutional reform and development held Wednesday
in the Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet members called to attend the workshop were given
briefings by Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu and National
Economic and Development Authority Director General Felipe Medalla
on the proposed economic reforms in the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
"We broke up into little clusters, subcommittees and all the
proposals and the processes were discussed by the Cabinet
members," Barican said, as he related the outcome of the workshop.
</P>
<P>
Barican said the task force will be required to prepare a
comprehensive Concord advisory plan based on the communication
plan of the Office of the Press Secretary and the results of the
Cabinet Workshop on Concord.
</P>
<P>
According to Barican, the task force will also coordinate and
monitor the implementation of the Concord advisory plan and
coordinate with the Preparatory Commission on Constitutional
Reforms.
</P>
<P>
The task force will be led by Trade and Industry Secretary Jose
Pardo as chairman. Its members include Executive Secretary Ronaldo
Zamora and other key members of the cabinet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
