<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Customs Smashes Biggest Syndicate of Pirated Discs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Customs officers of the Hong
Kong Intellectual Property Investigation Bureau Wednesday smashed
the biggest syndicate engaged in the production of pirated discs.
</P>
<P>
During the anti-piracy operation, the officers impounded three
production lines and a truck, and seized more than 1.6 million
pirated optical discs, totally worth 48 million HK dollars (6.15
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Acting on investigations, more than 120 Customs officers raided
the target factory and four storage centers. As a result, they
made the seizure and arrested nine men, aged 23 to 53.
</P>
<P>
According to the Prevention of Copyright Piracy Ordinance, the
maximum penalty for operating a CD factory without a valid license
is a fine of 1 million HK dollars (128,205 U.S. dollars) and four
years' imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
Customs officers have so far this year smashed eight unlicensed
optical discs factories, and impounded 12 production lines,
totally worth 61.5 million HK dollars (7.88 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In the first seven months of this year, the Customs officers
seized 8.8 million pirated optical discs with a market value of
160 million HK dollars (20.5 million U.S. dollars), and arrested 1,
381 suspects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
