<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Iraqi Minister of Commerce Mohamed Mahdi Saleh said
Iraq may conclude several transactions with Syria worth 300
million U.S. dollars in the sixth phase of U.N. oil-for-food
program.
</P>
<P>
After talks with his Syrian counterpart Mohamed Al Imadi on the
sidelines of the Damascus International Fair, Saleh said "steps
taken by Syria and Iraq over the past two years were steadily
activating bilateral trade cooperation between the two countries,"
the Arabic daily Al Hayat reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The two countries had a trade volume of 120 million dollars in
the second phase of the oil-for-food program, which has entered
the sixth phase.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Sources at the Tunisian Ministry of Foreign Investment
expect foreign investments in Tunisia this year to exceed a record
high of 600 million dinars (550 million dollars), surpassing
Tunisia's budget estimates.
</P>
<P>
The boom is attributed to the signing last Monday of a deal for
building an power plant in the suburban area of Radis, south of
the capital city Tunis. The project can attract 350 million dinars
(320 million dollars) in foreign investments, the Al Hayat reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In addition, some other important projects to be carried out
will involve 662 million dinars (600 million dollars) of foreign
investments.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Supertankers that carry over 180,000 tons of oil will
discharge part of its load into a smaller one at the Port of Suez
with the help of specialized loading and unloading companies.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Suez Canal Authority Ahmed Fadil said the two
tankers will transit the Canal together to Port Said where the
super tanker will recover its load, the Al Hayat reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Fadil said that the "Suez Canal Authority is granting
privileges in transit fees for these two tankers, and will collect
10 cents on every barrel of oil. Likewise, the fees of the
tugboats accompanying the two tankers will be exempted while they
transit the Canal."
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- An exhibition for Egyptian products is scheduled to be
opened on Saturday in Libreville, Gabon.
</P>
<P>
The eight-day event will be the biggest fair that has been
organized in the African countries by Egypt's General Authority
for International Fairs and Exhibitions, said Mohamed el-Sayed
Salah, the authority chairman.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-seven companies will exhibit food, ceramics, medicines
and medical appliances, house appliances and furniture in the
fair.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's total foreign debts stood at 28.224 billion
U.S. dollars last June according to the figure released by the
Ministry of Economy.
</P>
<P>
The foreign debts account for 31.5 percent of Egypt's gross
domestic product.
</P>
<P>
Most of the debts belong to long-term soft loans at interest
rates ranging from 0.75 percent to 2 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
