<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China City Luring Huge Overseas Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUZHOU, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Officials in Suzhou, a city in
east China, announced here today that the town has so far taken in
30 billion U.S. dollars from foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the city has over 7,000 overseas-funded companies, 4,
300 of which are operational. Multinationals like Dupont, Mobil,
Fujitsu and Samsung are among the investors.
</P>
<P>
Both local officials and foreign businessmen have attributed
Suzhou's success in luring foreign funds to the city's favorable
investment environment and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, these firms gained a combined
801 million yuan in profit, according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
The city government invests much of its revenue, about 8.7
billion yuan a year, into infrastructure, mainly in Suzhou
Industry Park.
</P>
<P>
In Suzhou, foreigners have their own hospitals, schools and a
special center for them to lodge complaints against any
impropriety of government officials.
</P>
<P>
The city is only 70 km away from the country's leading economic
center Shanghai, ranks seventh in GDP among all Chinese cities,
and has a large contingent of well-educated laborers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
