<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- The 3rd Syrian-European Union (EU) meeting started
Wednesday to discuss ways of promoting cooperation of small- and
medium-sized textile and ready-to-wear clothes companies between
Syria and European states.
</P>
<P>
Syrian Minister of Economy and Foreign Trade Mohamed Al Amadi
Wednesday inaugurated the meeting organized by the Syrian-EU
business center and the EU Commission envoy.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers reported Thursday that 35 foreign companies,
including those from European states, and 135 local firms are
participating in the meetings which will take place in Damascus,
Aleppo and Homs.
</P>
<P>
Textile is one of Syria's strategic industries and the second
largest source of revenues after petroleum. Weaving and textile
and ready-to-wear clothes industries take in 30 percent of the
total investments, bringing in some 53.9 billion liras (1.1
billion U.S. dollars). The textile industry also provides jobs for
36 percent of the industrial labor force.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Governor of Alexandria General Abdul Salam Mahgoub has
said that investments in petroleum projects now underway in
Alexandria have reached 20 billion pounds (about 5.8 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
In addition, the governor said investments in industrial and
free zones in Alexandria amounted to about 4 billion pounds (1.15
billion dollars), some 40 percent of overall industrial
investments, the Arabic daily Alam Al Yom reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Gowaili
has said that Egypt's non-petroleum imports reached 130.3 million
pounds (37.8 million dollars) in the first six months of this
year, an increase of 6 percent over the corresponding period of
last year.
</P>
<P>
Total imports, including petroleum products, amounted to 1.1
billion pounds (318 million dollars), an increase of 4.6 percent,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The Alam Al Yom reported Thursday that non-petroleum exports
during the first six months of this year has increased by about
356.9 million pounds (103.4 million dollars), a rise of 12.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, exports of petroleum and petroleum by-products have
declined by some 39.3 million pounds (11.4 million dollars), a
drop of 2.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
But the total exports have increased by about 403.6 million
pounds (116.9 million dollars), or 9.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Tourist arrivals in Egypt during the first six months
of the this year have reached about 2.15 million, who spent 12.9
million touristic nights, according to a monthly report of the
Egyptian Ministry of Economy.
</P>
<P>
Local press reported Thursday that southern and western
European countries are the biggest source of tourists to Egypt,
reaching about 1.323 million.
</P>
<P>
The Middle Eastern states occupied the second rank,
contributing about 387,000 tourists.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- A Jordanian official source at the Ministry of
Planning has said that debtors will consider rescheduling 350
million dollars of Jordan's debts in the second half of October.
</P>
<P>
Local press reported Thursday the total rescheduled debts will
be 1.150 billion dollars. He indicated that the Paris Club will
consider next year the rescheduling of 280 million dollars,
another 240 million dollars in 2001 and further 270 million
dollars in 2002.
</P>
<P>
The source pointed out that rescheduling Jordan's debts would
help lower the debts in the coming three years, alleviating the
burdens on State Budget and maintaining the country's reserves of
hard currencies.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, Jordan's overall external debts amount to
7 billion dollars, of which 4 billion are owed to the big seven
industrial countries, 3 billion to international finance
establishments and Arab funds. Japan is its biggest creditor.
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- The Sudanese Council of Ministers has approved an
agreement with the international fund for agricultural
development. Under the deal, Sudan will obtain a loan of 10.5
million dollars with a 10-year period of grace to finance the
rural development project in western Sudanese state of North
Kordofan.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports said Thursday that the project aims to
help local residents to establish economic infrastructure to
improve the income of farmers and sheperds, and achieve food
security in several districts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
