<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Probe Team Begins Work in Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 2 (Xinhua) - A United Nations team led by
former Swedish Premier Ingvar Carlson has arrived in Rwanda to
investigate the actions taken by the U.N. before and after the
1994 genocide, the Rwanda News Agency (RNA) reports Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Independent Inquiry commission was set up in May of this
year by the U.N. Security Council, on proposition by the Secretary
General Kofi Annan, and was given about six months to present its
report.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Carlson, the team is also comprised of former South
Korean Foreign Minister Han Sung-Joo, and Lieutenant General Rufus
M Kupolati from Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Carlson said the Inquiry commission aims "to give all the facts
we can on how this terrible genocide happened, how the
international community could let it happen and did not react
stronger and more rapidly'', and
</P>
<P>
"To draw conclusions for the future so hopefully never anything
like that could happen again."
</P>
<P>
Carlson told this to reporters upon arrival at Kanombe airport
of Rwanda's capital Kigali Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, Carlson said that it was not within the mandate of the
team to propose sanctions against individuals or member states who
would be found guilty.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Team started with looking into all materials available
on genocide, and very recently, it held a two-day seminar in
Geneva with international experts.
</P>
<P>
In the third and last phase, it will be visiting Rwanda,
Tanzania, Uganda, Washington, New York, Paris, Brussels, and other
places to meet people who can ''tell their own stories.''
</P>
<P>
 The United Nations, especially its current Secretary General
Kofi Annan, who at the time of genocide was U.N. Under-Secretary
General in charge of peace-keeping operations, has been seriously
criticized by Rwanda for its failure to intervene and stop the
genocide from April to July 1994.
</P>
<P>
While Hutu militia extremists were butchering people, the U.N.
decided to scale down its presence in Rwanda to around 200
soldiers, and withdrew the bulk of its force.
</P>
<P>
For its current stay in Rwanda, the U.N. Inquiry commission
will meet government officials, non-governmental organizations,
genocide survivors, and visit genocide sites.
</P>
<P>
The final report of the commission is expected to be presented
to the U.N. Secretary General before the end of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
