<HEADLINE> S. African Reserves Grow in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The gross gold and
foreign exchange reserves of the South African Reserve Bank grew
by almost 4.5 percent in August to 37.3 billion rand (6.1 billion
U.S. dollars), compared to 35.7 billion (5.85 billion dollars) in
the previous month.
</P>
<P>
"The increase in gross reserves was however not the result of
normal inflows but rather an increase in the use of foreign credit
lines," said Henry Flint, economist at Standard Bank Investment
Corporation. "The better than expected reserve figures compliment
the other (economic) data we have seen so far this week."
</P>
<P>
"Our positive trade performance and the growing foreign
interest in South African investments, especially equities, should
continue to support reserves," South African Press Association
Thursday quoted Flint as saying.
</P>
<P>
With most important data releases published for a while and a
stronger rand, the South African central bank may soon signal a
more rapid decline in the repo rate which will eventually filter
through to lower rates across the board, said the economist.
</P>
<P>
At the end of August, the use of foreign credit lines stood at
16.9 billion dollars compared to 15.2 billion dollars in July.
Net reserves remained virtually unchanged at 3.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Flint said the reserves could now almost cover three months of
imports, which is the internationally accepted norm. 
</P>
</TEXT>
