<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2,000-Year Old Noble's Tombs Found in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
found two noble's tombs, dating back to the Western Han Dynasty (
206 BC-24 AD) in Yuanling City in the western part of Hunan
Province.
</P>
<P>
The archaeologists, who are carrying out protective excavation
on the bigger tomb, said it had not been robbed before being
discovered in a construction area of the city.
</P>
<P>
The 15.3 by 12 meter tomb, located eight meters underground, is
at the same level as the famous Western Han tombs unearthed at
Mawangdui in Changsha, capital of Hunan.
</P>
<P>
The Mawangdui tombs were excavated in 1972. Objects unearthed
from the tombs include an intact woman's corpse, a jade suit
stitched with gold thread, exquisite lacquer, silk books, silk
paintings and bamboo slips with inscriptions on them.
</P>
<P>
The tomb is in three parts: a pit, chamber and entrance pathway,
and there are steps cut into the pit walls for access , according
to He Jiejun, head of the local archaeological research institute.
</P>
<P>
A large number of charcoal pieces, used as moisture proof
material, can be seen at the bottom of the pit, the expert said.
</P>
<P>
"There are three cypress boards covering the outer coffin," he
said. "On the two sides of the coffin, there are two wooden boxes
for containing objects buried with the dead," he went on, adding
that there is also a double door carved with characters indicating
North and South between the outer and inner coffin chamber.
</P>
<P>
The occupant of the tomb was probably a member of a large noble
family living in the region for three generations during the time
of the dynasty. "This will be confirmed after further excavation."
</P>
<P>
"The tombs will provide valuable clues for the study on funeral
systems and tomb construction in the early Han Dynasty," the
expert added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hundreds of People Begin Fleeing from E.Timor: Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of East Timorese have
fled to Belu and Timor Tengah Selatan districts in East Nusa
Tenggara province of Indonesia to avoid possible bloodshed in the
territory following a direct autonomy ballot held on August 30,
reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
East Nusa Tenggara Deputy Governor Johannis Pake Pani, in his
capacity as coordinator of the East Timorese refugee control
command post, said on Thursday a total of 645 East Timorese have
taken refuge in his province since Wednesday, the reports reaching
here from Dili, capital of East Timor, said.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday alone, he said, 265 East Timorese refugees fled to
East Nusa Tenggara via Wini port, and 58 others through Miomafo
subdistrict, Timor Tengah Utara district.
</P>
<P>
Some 140 East Timorese refugees arrived in East Nusa Tenggara
on Thursday through Wini port, he said.
</P>
<P>
A spate of violence took place in East Timor as vote counting
began for Monday's ballot on the future of the territory.
</P>
<P>
At least two persons were killed and there others injured in
the latest violence targeted at the U.N. Mission in East Timor
(UNAMET) on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said the local administration will pay full attention to the
refugees, regardless of whether they belong to the pro-integration
or pro-independence groups.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, two companies of policemen from Jakarta, capital of
Indonesia, arrived in Dili on Thursday to help secure the
territory following Wednesday's violence.
</P>
<P>
Observers said the post-voting period is the most crucial time
for clashing between the pro-integration and pro-independence
groups. The vote results which will decide whether East Timor, a
former Portuguese colony, enjoys a wide-ranging autonomy within
Indonesia or gets independence, are expected to come out on
September 7. 
</P>
</TEXT>
