<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Launch Nacala Corridor Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 2 (Xinhua)-- The Development Project of
Nacala Corridor jointly proposed by Mozambique and Malawi will
formally start in the first quarter of next year, Mozambican
Minister of Transport and Communications has said.
</P>
<P>
Paulo Muxanga made the announcement Wednesday at the Maputo
Airport following his visit to Malawi, where he had discussions
with his Malawi counterpart and potential investors and users of
the project.
</P>
<P>
The two governments agreed Tuesday at a meeting in Malawi on
advertising for two project directors, one Mozambican and one
Malawian, whose duty is to provide support to the joint technical
group of the two countries, Thursday' s Noticias newspaper quoted
Muxanga as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that before initiating the project, the two governments
will arrange for a meeting in October or November this year to
sign a memorandum.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the two countries are currently mapping out
plans on the development of railway, highway, port, industry and
tourism in this region, with the cost of port renovation estimated
at about 30 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Nacala is a fine natural port in northern Mozambique.
Currently, there is only one old and neglected railway there
linking Mozambique and Malawi together.
</P>
<P>
It is also reported that France may be one of donors of the
project, with Zambia as one of the potential users. 
</P>
</TEXT>
