<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Celebrating Centennial of Ancient City Discovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Scholars from China and abroad
will meet at the site of the city of Loulan in northwest China's
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region later this year for the
centennial of the discovery of the ancient city.
</P>
<P>
The event is being organized by the Xinjiang Loulan Research
Association, which expects to get people from the United States,
Japan, Taiwan, and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Loulan disappeared nearly 2,000 years ago but before that time
it had been one of the busiest commercial centers on the Silk Road
and an important contributor to the flow of goods to the West.
</P>
<P>
A Swedish archeologist discovered the ruins close to Lop Nur
Lake in 1900 and since that time, it has been attracting
adventurers and scholars from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
After the People's Republic of China was founded in 1949, the
site began getting better protection.
</P>
<P>
For the centennial, the scholars will gather at the site on
December 31 and erect a monument there to record its history and
events after it was discovered.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
