<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Last 80 Nigerian Soldiers in Liberia to Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is to withdraw its last
batch of peace-keeping soldiers from Liberia in late September,
Nigerian Foreign Minister Sule Lamido said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Some 80 Nigerian soldiers are still in Liberia as part of the
west African peace-keeping force ECOMOG charged with overseeing
the destruction of weapons remaining from the country's seven-year
civil war, the Post Express newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawing of the soldiers, demanded by Nigerian President
Olusegun Obasanjo, will bring an end to the country's nine-year
intervention in Liberia, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
In August 1990, then President Ibrahim Babangida sent thousands
of troops to Liberia to support embattled President Samuel Doe
against rebels led by Charles Taylor.
</P>
<P>
Doe was later killed and in 1997 Taylor was elected Liberian
President in a U.N. monitored election.
</P>
<P>
Before being elected to the presidency, Obasanjo had promised
to return home the last Nigerian troops from Liberia and Sierra
Leone, and to focus its government's energy on domestic economic
recovery.
</P>
<P>
Some 2,000 Nigerian peace-keeping troops in Sierra Leone were
Tuesday flown home following the signing of a peace agreement in
July, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
More troops are expected to be flown out of Sierra Leone in a
phased withdrawal expected to take around six months, reducing the
Nigerian contingent from around 10,000 to 1,000 men.
</P>
<P>
The last troops will be charged with overseeing the disarmament
agreed in the July peace accord in Lome, Togo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
