<HEADLINE> Pak Will Take into Account New Situation Before Making Decision on CTBT Issue: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Thursday said it
will take into account the "new situation" in the face of India's
recent nuclear doctrine before making any decision on the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) issue.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan cannot remain unmindful to this situation (after
India's announcement of nuclear program) and we have to take into
account all these factors before a final decision (on CTBT),"
Foreign Office Spokesman Tariq Altaf told foreign media here.
</P>
<P>
Last year both Pakistan and India agreed to sign the CTBT by
September 1999, but earlier this year India said it will not do so
before the completion of the general election which will be held
from September 5 to October 3.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, India launched earlier this month a "nuclear
doctrine" which targets the deployment and operationalization of
nuclear arms.
</P>
<P>
Altaf expressed Pakistan's concern over India's militarization
program.
</P>
<P>
"Recent developments have created a lot of complications and
the new situation, arising from India's militarization program,
has de-stabilized peace and security in the region," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
