<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jet Downed over Ethiopia May Have Veered Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A Johannesburg-bound jet
shot down over Ethiopia Sunday appeared to have veered off course
and strayed into a war zone, the South African embassy in Addis
Ababa said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Although we know how the plane was brought down, we can't say
how it ended up in a war zone or why it strayed off course," South
African Press Association quoted political counsellor Ajay Bramdeo
as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The two countries (Ethiopia and Eritrea) have been at war for
16 months. There is no way that either country would have granted
direct access to any plane from the territory of the other," the
counsellor said.
</P>
<P>
The flight plan of the Learjet 35A was from Luxor in Egypt to
Eritrean capital Asmara, to Perim in Djibouti, overhead Addis
Ababa to Nairobi where it was scheduled to land, according to
Linden Birns, a spokesman for aviation company ExecuJet.
</P>
<P>
However, the plane was shot down near the northern Ethiopian
town of Adwa, about 400 kilometers from Djibouti, Bramdeo said.
</P>
<P>
Birns said the aircraft had confirmed to Eritrean air traffic
controllers that it was en route to Djibouti shortly before
authorities lost radio contact with the jet.
</P>
<P>
"We can vouch that unless instructed to do otherwise, such
professional pilots would not have made the error to stray off
course over a war zone," he said.
</P>
<P>
"And even if they had, air traffic controllers would have
warned them," he added.
</P>
<P>
Birns said Ethiopian authorities would have to provide proof
that the aircraft had indeed crossed the war zone. "It is a handy
excuse at the moment."
</P>
<P>
The Learjet, which was registered in the United States, was on
its way to Johannesburg for refurbishment by ExecuJet. It was
being flown by South African-based British national Alan Lewis,
47, and Swede Anders Rors, 48.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia Wednesday accepted responsibility for shooting down
the plane. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
