<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dream of Doing Business at Home to Come True in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kongers' dream of doing
business elsewhere around the world at their homes will soon
become a reality, as an e-gateway project is expected to be
completed by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"Over the last three years, TNT has 'web enabled' most of its
major internal applications, and has laid the foundations for a
global e-commerce infrastructure," said Noud Leussink, a regional
manager of TNT's Customer Interface Technology (CIT) for Asia.
</P>
<P>
Leussink was speaking at a media workshop in Hong Kong Thursday,
unveiling TNT's latest and complete range of Internet services,
designed to reshape the marketplace for express distribution
services and secure TNT's leadership in Internet-based service
delivery.
</P>
<P>
TNT, one of the world's leading companies in global express
distribution, logistics and mail, has introduced e-gateway through
the CIT, offering online integration to complete the Internet
logistics system.
</P>
<P>
People are already able to do local e-commerce through the
Internet, but with the establishment of e-gateway supported by TNT,
they will have access to fast, efficient services worldwide,
explained Bryan Chan, general manager of the TNT Express Worldwide
(Hong Kong) Ltd.
</P>
<P>
"It's extremely encouraging," Chan said. TNT' technology is
designed to be integrated directly into the customer's supply
chain, streamlining operations for organization and allowing an
unprecedented control over the shipping and supply process, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Special Administrative Region government has made
efforts to promote the development of information technology and
the Internet and this has greatly helped the realization of e-
gateway, Chan said.
</P>
<P>
According to Lau Kam-hung, director of the Hong Kong government
's Information Technology Services, who spoke at an e-business
symposium in Melbourne Thursday, establishing an open and common
interface, as well as a public key infrastructure to enable
individuals, businesses and the government to interact through
digital networks easily and securely is one of the initiatives in
a move to put Hong Kong at the threshold to tomorrow's digital
world.
</P>
<P>
"The Internet has completely changed people's way of life since
its founding 30 years ago," Raymond To, senior account executive
of the API Prism Ltd., told the workshop.
</P>
<P>
To stressed that TNT's increasing focus on Internet commerce
and application is a direct reflection of their view on the
potential of the Asia-Pacific market, since Internet penetration
in Asia is being driven by businesses while in the United States
it was driven by individuals.
</P>
<P>
There will be a dramatic increase in the use of online business
in Asia in the next three years and by 2002, 70 percent of all
consignments in Asia will be handled electronically, To predicted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
