<HEADLINE> Team Starts Searching for Remains of W.W.II Bomber in SW China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- An American search team has
arrived at a mountain in southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region to look for the remains of the crew members
aboard a lost American bomber from the World War II.
</P>
<P>
On August 31, 1944, a B-24 bomber of the "Flying Tigers"
squadron crashed after bombing Japanese warships, killing all ten
crew members.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, local villagers found debris from the aircraft and the
remains of eight of the missing American airmen have subsequently
been recovered.
</P>
<P>
It is the fourth team that has been sent to the area for the
purpose, an official from the regional foreign affairs office told
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The team is composed of 12 servicemen, anthropologists and
linguists, while the local government has also sent 10 porters and
two doctors to travel with the American experts to the Mao'er
Mountain.
</P>
<P>
The search is scheduled to last three to five weeks and the
experts hope they could at least find something related to the
final two crew members.
</P>
<P>
Led by U.S. Gen. Claire Lee Chennault, the "Flying Tigers"
squadron was a voluntary American airlift operation which helped
the Chinese in their struggle against the Japanese aggression.
</P>
</TEXT>
