s comments that he had betrayed the people of Northern Ireland, in
return, accused Hague and others of undermining the already
troubled peace process in the province.
</P>
<P>
"Before people say 'let's pull the whole process to bits',
which is effectively what the Conservatives are saying, they
should really think about the future of Northern Ireland, the
children of Northern Ireland and whether it is really a
responsible thing to do," Blair told the Times in an interview.
</P>
<P>
The Conservatives and politicians from Northern Ireland's
Protestant majority have attacked Northern Ireland Secretary Mo
Mowlam for ruling that the IRA's two-year-old ceasefire was still
intact despite reports the guerrilla group was linked to a Belfast
murder and a U.S. gun-running plot.
</P>
<P>
Blair accused Hague of breaking a long-standing bipartisan
policy on Northern Ireland between Britain's main parties.
</P>
<P>
He urged politicians from across the sectarian divide in
Northern Ireland to set aside bitter recriminations and join a new
peace push next week.
</P>
<P>
"The idea nothing has been gained through the peace process is
absurd," he said. "Parts of the media and parts of the
Conservative Party did not want the Good Friday agreement to
succeed and did not believe in it."
</P>
<P>
Last year's Good Friday peace agreement has run into trouble
because of a deadlock over guerrilla disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Blair said finding a way forward was his most urgent priority.
