<HEADLINE> Indonesia Sends Police Companies to East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Two companies of policemen
from Jakarta arrived in Dili, capital of East Timor, on Thursday
to help secure the territory following the direct ballot on August
30.
</P>
<P>
The 200 policemen arrived in Dili aboard two Hercules transport
planes of the Indonesian Air Force at noon, according to the
Antara News Agency.
</P>
<P>
"The police have two main tasks following the popular
consultation -- to help create a conducive situation and to
safeguard the process and result of vote count of the ballot,"
East Timor Police Chief Col. Timbul Silaen said in a written
address to the police companies.
</P>
<P>
There have been plans to send five police companies to East
Timor after the ballot, Antara said, adding that it is not known
when the other three companies will arrive.
</P>
<P>
There are 28 police companies under the command of the East
Timor Police.
</P>
<P>
A spate of violence took place in East Timor as the United
Nations began counting the votes from Monday's ballot on the
future of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
At least two persons were killed and three others injured in
the latest violence targeted at the U.N. Mission in East Timor
(UNAMET) on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
National Police spokesman Brig. Gen. Togar Sianipar said here
Wednesday that in anticipation of post-ballot violence, a Mobile
Brigade unit was deployed from Kupang to Atambua, bordering East
Timor and East Nusa Tenggara. If necessary, five units will be
sent to East Timor, he added.
</P>
<P>
Defying fears of massive violence, 98.6 percent of the about
450,000 registered voters showed up for the ballot.
</P>
<P>
The direct ballot will determine whether East Timor, a former
Portuguese colony, will enjoy wide-ranging autonomy within
Indonesia or get independence. East Timor was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976, but the move was never recognized by the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
Vote results are expected to come out on September 7. 
</P>
</TEXT>
