<HEADLINE> 2,700-Year-Old Relics Found in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
found more than 3,000 pieces of pottery, jade and bronze articles,
dating back to the Spring and Autumn Period (770 B.C.-476 B.C.),
in Houma City in Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The articles were unearthed from 950 tombs and 900 pits used in
ancient ceremonies in a 500,000-sq-m ruins, which were discovered
at a construction site of the city early last year.
</P>
<P>
Among the relics, the most rare is a pressurized bronze cooking
vessel that even contains the remains of food from ancient time.
</P>
<P>
The well-preserved tombs and objects inside will provide
valuable clues for archaeological research into the Jin State, an
ancient kingdom of the Spring and Autumn Period with Houma as its
capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Bid Farewell to Hunger (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to official data, spending on food by agricultural
workers accounted for 69 percent of their income in the early
1950s, but had dropped to 53 percent by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
However, their spending on education, recreation and services
grew to 10 percent, with the livable housing space rising to 23.7
square meters per household.
</P>
<P>
Bian Cuihua, a baby-sitter in Beijing from rural areas in
neighboring Hebei Province, said, "I have enough to eat and wear
at home. I came to Beijing mainly to broaden my view."
</P>
<P>
In the southeastern coastal areas, which took the lead in
developing rural businesses in China, city dwellers saw with envy
the building of elegantly designed houses by farmers, their sedan
cars and fashionable clothes. And it is now hard to tell a farmer
from a urban resident.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 20 years, the net income of farmers nationwide
has grown by 10 percent on average, but the growth rate has varied
in different regions due to unbalanced economic development.
</P>
<P>
In eastern China, farmers' income has jumped 19.5 fold, while
the figure is 14.6 fold and 11.7 fold, respectively, in central
and western regions.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has intensified its efforts to develop
the vast western region, especially western mountainous areas
which are now home to most of the remaining impoverished people.
</P>
<P>
This year, the central government will spend a record 28.4
billion yuan in poverty relief, hoping to reach its goal of
banishing poverty for farmers by the end of the century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suicide Bombing Kills Tamil Politician in N.Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A suicide bombing on Thursday
noon killed at least two people in northern Sri Lanka, including a
senior Tamil politician, informed sources said.
</P>
<P>
Manikkadasam, vice president of the People's Liberation
Organization of Tamil Eelam (PLOTE) was blown up by a woman
suicide bomber in the party's office in Vavuniya, some 250
kilometers north of Colombo, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Manikkadasam, also the party's military wing
leader, was killed during a meeting in his office.
</P>
<P>
A PLOTE's district military leader was also killed in the
explosion.
</P>
<P>
Nobody has yet claimed responsibility for the suicide bombing.
But police believed that it was an operation of separatist
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE).
</P>
<P>
PLOTE has been helping the government in its 16-year old fight
against the LTTE rebels who demand a separate Tamil homeland in
the north and east of the country.
</P>
<P>
LTTE rebels, notorious for launching suicide bombing, have also
been blamed for the killing of Neelan Thiruchelvam, a leading
Tamil lawmaker and vice president of the Tamil United Liberation
Front (TULF) in late July. 
</P>
