<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Slams Banks Over Minimum Balance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi has criticized major banking institutions for locking out
small depositors with the imposition of high minimum balances.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation newspaper Thursday quoted Moi as saying that
the practice had forced people especially those in the rural
areas to close their accounts due to the inability to meet the
high balances.
</P>
<P>
"As a result, most people in the rural areas do not have
adequate banking facilities," Moi said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Major banks in Kenya introduced high minimum balances for
current and savings account holders recently. The Kenyan
government holds less than 50 percent of shares in a few banks.
</P>
<P>
Over 40 percent of Kenyans live under poverty line, according
to official statistics. 
</P>
