<HEADLINE> Bangladesh MP Urges Asia to Secure Destiny of Mankind </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A member of the Bangladeshi
Parliament said here Thursday that with nearly two-thirds of
humanity on its soil, Asia has an abiding, natural and moral
responsibility to secure the destiny of mankind.
</P>
<P>
Ali Ashraf made this statement in his keynote paper presented
at the Asian Parliamentarians' Conference for Peace and
Cooperation, which started here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The 20th century has been a violent and painful one -- more so
in Asia. Since World War II, Asia has witnessed more full-blown
wars than all the other continents put together," noted Ashraf,
who is also chairman of Bangladesh's Parliamentary Standing
Committee on the Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
"We, the parliamentarians as people's representatives can save
our states and our people from the meaningless pursuit of
belligerence," he told the conference.
</P>
<P>
On the role of parliamentarians in maintaining human security,
Ashraf said, "We must act together to bridge the gaps between
dissenting and discontent minds, diffuse tension, discourage
militarism, avert conflict and so on."
</P>
<P>
All the people of the world want peace and security, he said,
pointing out, "To ensure security most of the developed countries
are making nuclear weapons spending a great amount of their
wealth, but they are very much ignorant about the fact that arms
can never bring peace or security."
</P>
<P>
"Only the removal of arms or disarmament can make the world
safe, secure and peaceful," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Some 105 members of parliament from 33 Asian countries and 38
members of civil societies of these countries are attending the
four-day conference, which was initiated by Bangladesh and is
funded by the Bangladeshi government and the U.N. Development
Program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
