<HEADLINE> Sudanese MPs to Visit Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Two members of the Sudanese
Parliament are scheduled to arrive in Uganda Thursday for a visit
connected with the longstanding problem of abduction of children
by rebels in the northern part of Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Kagole Kivumbi, spokesman to the Ugandan Parliament, told
Xinhua in a telephone interview Thursday morning that the Sudanese
MPs were coming for the visit, but they were not invited by the
Ugandan legislature.
</P>
<P>
"I am not aware that they are invited by the Parliament. They
can be invited by some individual MPs here," he said.
</P>
<P>
A newspaper report Thursday said that the United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) is coordinating the visit.
</P>
<P>
Absolom Ongom, chairperson of the Acholi Parliamentary Group,
was quoted as saying that the Acholi MPs would meet the Sudanese
in the UNICEF office here later in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese legislators would visit Kitgum and Gulu, two
northern districts subject to frequent attacks by the rebels of
the Lord Resistance Army (LRA) since 1986.
</P>
<P>
The LRA rebels, spearheaded by Joseph Kony and allegedly based
in southern Sudan, have made abductions and killings in northern
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Sudan have accused each other of backing their rebel
groups in their respective countries. The two neighbors severed
their relations in
April 1995. 
</P>
