<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Seek Better Ecology along China's Longest Inland River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Top Chinese scientists have
called for the improvement of the ecological environment along the
Tarim River, China's longest inland river in the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
According to a consultation report released by the Chinese
Academy of Sciences (CAS), China's leading science institute, the
deteriorating ecological environment along the Tarim River affects
the whole region of Xinjiang, and as a result sand storms will
spread to northwest and north China and farther areas outside the
country.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,321 kilometers long, the Tarim River flows through
Xinjiang, and is regarded by the local people as the region's "
mother river". Many historic sites including the ancient kingdom
of Loulan are dotted along the river.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xinshi, an academician of the CAS, said that because of
improper water utilization, 320 kilometers of the river have dried
up, and the underground water in the lower reaches of the river
has dropped 18 meters since the 1950's.
</P>
<P>
The forest area of a poplar species growing in the desert
decreased by 47,000 hectares from 1958 to 1995, and a large area
of farmland was turned into desert.
</P>
<P>
Observation data from the meteorological department show that
the precipitation amount in the valley of the river has remained
the same over the past four decades.
</P>
<P>
Scientists attribute the reason for the drying up of the river
to large scale reclamation of wasteland, improper use of water in
the upper reaches, inefficient irrigation, and lack of water
facilities.
</P>
<P>
In the consultation report, scientists have suggested
harnessing the middle reaches of the river, and building dykes and
canals. The run-off of the river is expected to increase by more
than two billion cubic meters as a result.
</P>
<P>
The construction of water projects along the Tarim River will
also benefit the local economy in the northwestern region of China
and help narrow the gap between the region and the developed
coastal areas, said the report.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
