<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sees Irreplaceable Role for Conference on Disarmament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Conference on Disarmament (
CD), as a multilateral disarmament negotiating body, is
irreplaceable in terms of its status and role, the Chinese
ambassador for disarmament affairs, Li Changhe, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Even though it has not been able to get down to treaty
negotiations for the time being, the conference can still function
as an important forum where dialogue can be conducted on major
issues of international peace and security, and on some specific
disarmament items," Li said at a CD plenary.
</P>
<P>
He said that the CD could help enhance mutual understandings
and explore possibilities for negotiations on certain issues.
</P>
<P>
"It is our hope that the international situation could improve
and delegations accommodate each other's concerns in a practical
and flexible manner in order to reach an early agreement on a
comprehensive and balanced program of work next year," Li told the
plenary as the CD's 1999 session was about to be concluded.
</P>
<P>
The admission of five new members on August 5 was the major
progress of the 1999 session, Li said. The new members are Ecuador,
Ireland, Kazakhstan, Malaysia and Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
Li said that a series of developments this year in
international peace and security have exerted profound negative
impact on international relations, the confidence and security
perceptions of states, which in turn inevitably affected the
international disarmament process.
</P>
<P>
The divergence among member states on the CD's program of work
should not be seen as procedural in nature, but rather a
reflection of differences over the priorities for disarmament
agenda, he said.
</P>
<P>
In formulating its program of work, the CD should take this
fact into consideration and accommodate the concerns of all member
states to the largest extent possible in a comprehensive and
balanced manner, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Necessary political will and flexibility is required from all
sides," Li said. "The current stalemate manifests the necessity
for further efforts in this regard." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
