<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Commercial Bank is
hoping to find a foreign strategic partner by the end of this year
to reverse the bank's recent misfortunes.
</P>
<P>
The bank's general manager Ernest Saina said Wednesday that the
search for a foreign bank to invest in his bank was a top
priority, adding "we have already sent feelers to potential
banks."
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation newspaper Thursday quoted the general manager
as saying a strategic partner would bring in global benefits,
access to technology, funds and management.
</P>
<P>
The commercial bank, one of the five largest banks in Kenya,
has been hurt by bad and doubtful debts, and its pre-tax profits
slumped to 1.4 billion shillings (around 20 million U.S. dollars)
in 1998 from 4.1 billion shillings in 1997.
</P>
<P>
For the first half of this year, the bank only posted a pre-tax
profit of 393 million shillings (some 5.6 million dollars)
compared with 1.6 billion shillings in the 1998 same period.
</P>
<P>
It is also reported that the bank's shares have plummeted 46.6
percent in the last 12 months to 39 shillings on Tuesday from 73
shillings. 
</P>
