<HEADLINE> Share Prices End Lower on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Share prices closed lower on
Singapore Stock Market Thursday weighed down by lingering concern
over a U.S. interest rate hike.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) lost 4.13 points to end
at 2,118.21 in thin trading.
</P>
<P>
The total turnover increased slightly to 216.87 million shares
valued at 415.75 million Singapore dollars (247.15 million U.S.
dollars). Decliners led advancers by 271 to 54 with 122 counters
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Gen Int remained at the top of the volume list with a turnover
of 25.36 million units. It was followed by AFP which had 19.85
million shares done. Hotung ranked third on the actives chart as
it had 15.69 million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Robinson led gainers of the day going up 50 cents to finish at
5.8 Singapore dollars. PacCent and UOB picked up 40 cents to close
at 8 and 13 Singapore dollars separately. AsiaMedic edged up 32
cents to end at 2.73 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, C&AMP;C was the biggest loser of the day as it
dropped 75 cents to close at 9.1 Singapore dollars. NatElect was
down 45 cents to finish at 7.8 Singapore dollars. OCBC and Venture
shed 20 cents to end at 11.3 and 15.5 Singapore dollars
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Dealers noted U.S. interest rate concerns continued to
dominate the sentiment on the market and trading activity failed
to bounce back after the August volume plummeted to its lowest
level in five months.
</P>
<P>
They said the market was looking to U.S. employment data due
out on Friday for clue on whether the U.S. Federal Reserve would
raise rates again when it meets early next months.
</P>
<P>
They also noted that U.S.-dollar denominated stocks dominated
market activities and blamed the fall of Circle &AMP; Carriage (C&AMP;C)
on rumors that the company had lost its Mercedes Benz
distributorship, which the company rejected. 
</P>
