<HEADLINE> Beijing Park Marks Postal Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A new park opened in Beijing
today to commemorate the 22nd Universal Postal Congress (UPC)
which is being held in China for the first time.
</P>
<P>
International delegates to the congress attended the opening
ceremony of the park located beside the site of an ancient post
office in a northern suburb of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Liu Liqing, postmaster general of China's State Post Bureau (
SPB) said that the particular location of the park is meaningful.
He said that postal services have made great contributions to the
progress of civilization in the past and will further promote
social progress under the joint efforts of the members of the
Universal Postal Union (UPU).
</P>
<P>
Thomas Leavey, director general of the International Bureau of
the UPU, said that environmental protection has received great
attention at the congress.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the postal sector handles a very large portion of
the earth's paper and uses hundreds of thousands of motor vehicles
for collecting and delivering mail, he said that postal services
worldwide have a heavy ecological and economic responsibility.
</P>
<P>
"I am proud to say that in recent years, postal services have
come to realize the effect of their business on the environment
and the need to act in a responsible way," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the opening of the tree packed park is a very good
example of such efforts.
</P>
<P>
Liu and Leavey unveiled a monument in the park engraved with
the name of the 189 member countries of the UPU.
</P>
<P>
The international delegates planted a tree on behalf of each of
their countries.
</P>
<P>
A delegate from Cote Divoire in Africa said that each tree
planted in the park represents the goodwill of the people from a
member of the UPU.
</P>
<P>
"As we are applying to be host of the next UPC, our country is
thinking of holding similar activities to this," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
