<HEADLINE> Tanzanians Say Bodies Found at Plane Crash Scene </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman for U.S.
embassy in Dar es Salaam said Thursday that Tanzanian villagers
had found bodies at the scene where a small plane carrying 10 U.S.
tourists crashed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. rescuers have not reached the crash scene yet because
it lies in a hilly, steep area, so the fate of the tourists have
yet to be established, Dudley Sims, Director of United States
Information Service in Dar es Salaam, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Arusha Regional Commissioner, Daniel ole Njoolay, will take a
helicopter with policemen and doctors later Thursday to inspect
the scene, a local government official told Xinhua over telephone.
</P>
<P>
"It's difficult for a car to reach the scene because the plane
crashed in a steep mountain," said the official who declined to be
identified.
</P>
<P>
The plane, which crashed Wednesday morning, was carrying six
male and four female U.S. tourists from the world-famous Serengeti
National Park to the Kilimanjaro Airport in northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
On board the aircraft, which went down some 12 miles away from
the 14, 979-foot Mount Meru, the fifth highest in Africa, were
also a Tanzanian tour guide and a pilot. 
</P>
</TEXT>
