<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Post Prospers After Return to Motherland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong postal services have
enjoyed greater influence in the postal world since Hong Kong
returned to the motherland in 1997, according to a senior postal
official in the special administrative region.
</P>
<P>
During an interview with Xinhua, Allan Chiang, deputy
postmaster general of Hong Kong Post, said that since 1997 Hong
Kong has had much more opportunities to participate in
international postal meetings than ever before under the "one
country, two systems" policy.
</P>
<P>
He is one of the ten representatives from the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) attending the ongoing 22nd Universal
Postal Congress (UPC) in Beijing as members of the Chinese
delegation.
</P>
<P>
He describes the cooperative relations between Hong Kong Post
and postal services on the mainland of China as "brotherly" which
began long before the 1997 handover.
</P>
<P>
Express Mail Services (EMS) is the number one postal exchange
between Hong Kong and the mainland in terms of volume, followed by
ordinary mail. Pointing out that mainland customs have greatly
supported and assisted the relay of mail to and from Hong Kong, he
said that the volume of EMS between the two places increased by 15
percent after 1997.
</P>
<P>
"Delivery time of EMS has also been cut to two days, which is
an unprecedented speed," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the philately service is also an important area of
cooperation between Hong Kong and the inland, with a two-way trade
volume of 46 million Hong Kong dollars every year.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong people are buying one million Hong Kong dollars
worth of stamps from the mainland every year. Taking into
consideration the population of Hong Kong, it is quite a
significant figure," he said.
</P>
<P>
Though Hong Kong Post still remains as a government institution,
the postal service on China's mainland has become a corporation
that has a certain independence from the postal administration.
</P>
<P>
"It is much more flexible in offering services than in Hong
Kong," Chiang said. "And its operations are highly commercialized,
which is very good," he added.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that the postal services, both in Hong
Kong and on the mainland, have a bright future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
