<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Encouraging Use of Water-Saving Irrigation Methods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, September 2 (Xinhua) -- China has begun changing from
its old way of flooding fields to a new water-saving irrigation
system, which was being used on about 15.3 million hectares of
land at the end of 1998, according to the Water Resources Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government is placing great importance on this and
other methods and is encouraging farmers to use them, the ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
In a recent visit to areas along the Yellow River, President
Jiang Zemin said that saving water and changing from flooding
fields to more intensive cultivation is a priority item. To this
end, China has earmarked more than 25 billion yuan for encouraging
the use of the new method since 1996.
</P>
<P>
For the past three years, 15 billion cubic meters of water have
been saved annually because of this project, which is equal to
building 150 large reservoirs that would cost billions of yuan.
China's total grain output at the same time went from 466.5
billion kilograms to 490 billion.
</P>
<P>
Water shortages are still a major hindrance to national
economic development and social advancement, so China will
continue to improve irrigation methods. By 2010, water-saving
irrigation will be used on 34 million hectares, according to Zhang
Chunyuan, vice-minister of water resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia All Set to Deal with Y2K </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia has attained
almost full Y2K-compliance to deal with the so-called millennium
bug, Energy, Communications and Multimedia Minister Leo Moggie
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The actual situation in the country with regard to the Y2K is
that we're convinced that between December 31, 1999 and January 1,
2000, it'll be business as usual," he said when briefing the media
here on the state of the country's readiness for the Y2K.
</P>
<P>
"I believe this Y2K problem, widely feared to arise on that
day, will not occur and as such there is no cause for the public
to panic. We're moving towards total preparedness by that date by
concentrating on the critical sectors," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia activated its National Y2K Contingency Plan Operation
Center Wednesday to coordinate public and private sector efforts
in tackling the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
The national operation center aims at monitoring all situations
linked with the Y2K issue in nine critical sectors -- energy,
transportation, oil and gas, government, health, water supply,
sewerage, communications, and banking and finance.
</P>
<P>
The center will be constantly updated with information relating
to the Y2K disruption and disseminate information to the public on
the Y2K issue through various media as well as decide on
appropriate responses and direct necessary action. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Bid Farewell to Hunger (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Great changes have taken place in China's rural areas over the
past 50 years, especially since 1978 when the household contract
responsibility system was implemented and farmers were allowed to
farm their own land.
</P>
<P>
With good consecutive grain harvests and the mushrooming of
rural businesses, Chinese farmers no longer have to worry about
starvation and care only about how much more money they can earn.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Ke, an official of Lingbi's Weiji Town, where Zhang lives,
said that it used to be the poorest region in the county, with
annual per capita income less than 100 yuan 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
"The figure has risen to 1,750 yuan and more than 90 percent of
households have bought farm vehicles and almost every family has a
TV set," he said.
</P>
<P>
The National Bureau of Statistics indicates that the average
net income of farmers nationwide has soared to 2,162 yuan in 1998
from 44 yuan in 1949, when the People's Republic of China was
founded.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of impoverished people dropped to 42
million last year from 250 million in 1978, accompanied by a
remarkable improvement in the quality of life and the living
environment of farmers.
</P>
<P>
By 1998, over 95 percent of villages across the country had
access to highways, some 70 percent to telephone services, and
more than 95 percent to electricity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Bid Farewell to Hunger (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Editor's note: This year marks
the 50th anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of
China. Over the past five decades, China's achievements in all
economic sectors have attracted worldwide attention.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua News Agency is to release about 20 stories about the
nation's economy. The first of the series was released on August
17. This is the thirteenth.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-five year old farmer Zhang Desheng never imagined when he
was a youngster that he would be eating meat or wheat-flour bread
every day but these have become common foods for his family now.
</P>
<P>
Zhang lives in Lingbi County, in the north of east China's
Anhui Province, a place which used to be hit alternatively by
droughts and floods; and a place where farmers made a meager
living by growing sweet potatoes.
</P>
<P>
"Sweet potato and sweet potato, no one can survive without
sweet potato", is an old proverb that best depicted the life of
local agricultural workers in the past. They had almost nothing to
eat except sweet potato and meat was a rare delicacy.
</P>
<P>
Now, Zhang lives with his youngest son, who works in a village
fodder plant, and helps his daughter-in-law to grow wheat, cotton
and vegetables, while raising four pigs and dozens of hens.
</P>
<P>
"We have several dishes for each meal and sweet potatoes have
become fodder," Zhang said, grinning, "I can even enjoy my
favorite Sizhou opera from TV every night."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Several hundred anti-independence militiamen launched a
bloody chase against the pro-independent militants in the
Indonesian province of East Timor Wednesday afternoon around the
headquarters of the United Nations Mission in East Timor (UNAMET)
in Dili. At least two persons were killed -- one was shot, the
other killed with axe -- and several houses burnt in the area
surrounding the U.N. mission.
</P>
<P>
-- In Sweden, about 63,000 people were sterilized between 1935
and 1975 as the Swedish authorities were trying to eliminate what
they considered to be "dregs" in order not to block the collective
development of the country. Some of the victims are now asking for
compensations from the government.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- For Russians, the custom of placing its money in security in
the West is not new. While the latest affair of International
Monetary Fund (IMF) is making a scandal, in which from 4.2 to 15
billion U.S. dollars of IMF aid was hijacked, it is estimated that
the money which escaped Russia in the past five years amounted to
138 billion U.S. dollars, most of them through operations of
imports and exports.
</P>
<P>
-- India will hold on Sunday its third legislative elections in
three years. The ruling BJP is expected to beat the Congress Party
of Sonia Gandhi. The war against Pakistan in Kashmir has lifted
the image of Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee, the key figure
of BJP who has made India enter the club of nuclear arms. 
</P>
