<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Present Political Package Before Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government is
keen to present before parliament a political package aiming to
resolve the long drawn-out ethnic war, said Minister of Media
Mangala Samaraweera Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Samaraweera, who is also Cabinet spokesman, told a news
conference that President Chandrika Kumaratunga will present the
package "as soon as possible" if some minor differences of
electoral reforms are ironed out.
</P>
<P>
He said that President Kumaratunga had instructed Justice
Minister G.L. Peiris to make legislative preparations for the
political package.
</P>
<P>
The ruling People's Alliance (PA) government and the main
opposition United National Party (UNP) on Wednesday started a new
round of bipartisan talks to work towards a mutually acceptable
peace proposal.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has been plagued by a 16-year old civil war fought
between the government and the Tamil rebels who demand a separate
homeland in the north and east of the country.
</P>
<P>
President Kumaratunga unveiled a power-sharing political
package four years ago to resolve the conflict through non-violent
means but it has been shelved due to the lack of bipartisan
consensus.
</P>
<P>
The government had hoped to present the package before
parliament last month but was delayed again for fears that it
would not receive a mandatory two-thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
Samaraweera said that most of the UNP lawmakers would support
the government's political package once it is tabled before
parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
