<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Achieves 93 Percent Literacy Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has made progress in its
campaign to eliminate illiteracy since the country declared
independence on September 2, 1945.
</P>
<P>
Now as many as 93 percent of Vietnam's 76.3 million people are
literate, compared with only 10 percent in 1945, the Vietnam News
Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
By June 1999, 52 of the country's 61 provinces and cities had
met the national standard in illiteracy elimination. This means
that 538 of 597 districts and 9,611 of 10,299 wards and communes
have met the national standards.
</P>
<P>
According to the standards in illiteracy elimination set by the
Ministry of Education and Training in 1995, an individual is
literate if he or she finishes the third grade of the five-grade
primary education; a commune will be recognized as meeting the
national standard if 90 percent of its 15-35 year olds (15-25 year
olds for mountainous areas) are literate; and a city or province
will meet the national standard if 90 percent of its districts and
communes meet the standard for them.
</P>
<P>
Now, the Vietnamese government is still making efforts to
eliminate illiteracy in the remaining nine mountainous and remote
provinces. Illiterate people in the nine provinces number 181,700.
</P>
<P>
The nine provinces have received almost half of the 40 billion
Vietnamese dong (about 2.86 million U.S. dollars) from the
national budget for this year's illiteracy elimination and primary
education program.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government has approved additional fundings of
7.5 billion Vietnamese dong (about 536,000 dollars) to help the
poorer five provinces of Lai Chau, Ha Giang, Lao Cai, Kon Tum and
Soc Trang to carry out the task. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
