<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan, South Korea Agree to Strengthen Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi and visiting South Korean Prime Minister Kim Jong Pil
agreed Thursday to further strengthen bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference after their talks, Obuchi
said he reconfirmed with Kim "the importance of building up future-
oriented relations" between Japan and South Korea by steadily
implementing the action plan the two countries adopted during a
state visit to Japan by South Korean President Kim Dae Jung last
October.
</P>
<P>
Specifically, Obuchi said he and Kim agreed to begin full-
fledged negotiations later this month toward concluding a
bilateral investment treaty, and to start consultations between
aviation authorities toward improving transportation when the two
countries co-host the 2002 World Cup soccer finals.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers also agreed to boost various exchange
programs between the two countries in 2002.
</P>
<P>
Kim, who arrived here Wednesday for a five-day official visit,
renewed Seoul's invitation to Japanese Emperor Akihito to visit
South Korea for the first time before the 2002 World Cup. Obuchi
replied that Japan intends to work on improving the environment
toward realizing the visit.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi conveyed his intention to attend the second round of
bilateral consultations involving a full range of cabinet
ministers to be hosted by South Korea on October 23-24 on Cheju
Island.
</P>
<P>
The first round of bilateral consultation, hosted by Tokyo last
November in Kagoshima, southwestern Japan, was attended by 11
cabinet ministers, including Kim and Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also agreed to beef up cooperation in such
multilateral bodies as the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum
and the World Trade Organization, and to continue working together
on global issues including the reduction of greenhouse gases,
Obuchi said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
