<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gender Gap Exists in U.S. Internet Usage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Men and women in the
United States approach the Internet with a different mind-set,
according to an on-line survey released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Most women tend to check e-mail and gather information about a
topic of interest on the Web more often than men, while men are
twice as likely to go to the Web to transfer or download files
than women, said the survey report from PC Data, a leading
Internet research firm specializing in Web audience measurement.
</P>
<P>
The firm had reportedly surveyed more than 2,800 Internet users
in early August.
</P>
<P>
Eighty percent of women are more likely to surf the Web with a
specific task or objective in mind than men, and are more likely
to use page links as both a navigation method and a source for
site information. Men are more likely to use search engines for
navigation and site information.
</P>
<P>
In addition, men and women shop for different items on the Web.
Men are more likely to purchase computer software and hardware.
Women are more likely to use the Internet to shop for greeting
cards and music. Both men and women are equally interested in
shopping for books on-line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
