<HEADLINE> Rescuers Difficult to Reach Plane Crash Scene </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Arusha Regional Commissioner, Daniel ole Njoolay, will take a
helicopter with policemen and doctors later Thursday to inspect
the scene, a local government official told Xinhua over telephone.
</P>
<P>
"It's difficult for a car to reach the scene because the plane
crashed in a steep mountain," said the official who declined to be
identified.
</P>
<P>
The small plane, which crashed Wednesday morning, was carrying
six male and four female U.S. tourists from the world-famous
Serengeti National Park to the Kilimanjaro Airport in northern
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
On board the Cessna aircraft, which went down some 12 miles
away from the 14,979-foot Mount Meru, the fifth highest in Africa,
also included a Tanzanian tour guide and a pilot.
</P>
<P>
Mount Meru, often surrounded by cloud, is a part of the Arusha
National Park located some 45 kilometers from the Arusha town in
the Arusha Region.
</P>
<P>
U.S. embassy staffs in Tanzanian and Kenya are also heading
toward the scene, Director of the United States Information
Service in Tanzania, Dudley Sims, told Xinhua on Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
The acting permanent secretary in the Ministry of Natural
Resources and Tourism, R.P. Kabende, left here Thursday morning
for Arusha to handle issues related to the incident.
</P>
<P>
Rescue efforts using helicopters have started since Wednesday
after the plane crashed but were hampered by foggy weather.
</P>
<P>
The Serengeti park draws tens of thousands of tourists every
year who came to see its wide range of big game animals and the
annual migration of millions of gnus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
