<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Navy Helicopters to Be Equipped with Tele-guidance Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Royal Malaysian Navy
(RMN) Thursday signed a contract with Alenia Marconi for the
supply of tele-guidance systems for its ordered Super Lynx
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
The contract for the tele-guidance systems at a cost of 24.2
million ringgit (about 6.368 million U.S. dollars) was signed here
by Defense Ministry's Secretary-general Hashim Meon on behalf of
the Malaysian government and Alenia Marconi's Far East area
manager Sergio Cavicchi, Bernama news agency said quoting a
Defense Ministry official.
</P>
<P>
The helicopters will have the primary role of supporting the
Lekiu class warship weapons systems and also those of the four
Italian Fincantieri corvettes to allow the course of long-range
anti-ship missiles such as the Otomat Mk2 with a range of 150
kilometers to be controlled or changed during the flight path and
to guide it to the target with accuracy.
</P>
<P>
The system will allow optimum operation of the Otomat missile
for its long range capability when launched from the Italian-made
Laksamana class corvettes, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement for the supply of six Super Lynx naval
helicopters is expected to be signed between the Malaysian
government and the British helicopter maker GKN Westland Friday,
Bernama said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another contract for the supply of a number of .50
caliber machine guns worth 3.2 million ringgit (about 0.84 million
U.S. dollars) for the new helicopters was also signed Thursday by
the ministry's secretary-general and Mohamad Maydien Ahmad of
Syarikat Silest Sdn Bhd, acting on behalf of FN Herstal of
Belgium, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The machine guns will be used to support boarding and
anti-piracy roles of the helicopters and also to support missions
carried out by the Navy's commando unit -- the Naval Special
Operations Force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
