<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi announced Wednesday that the Mombasa Port will not be
privatized but a corporate partner will be found to run certain
services to improve the efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The president made the remark when he was giving a speech at
the opening of the Post Bank regional office in Coast Province and
launching the bank's denominations of premium bonds in the
southeastern Mombasa City.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by local media Thursday as saying that the
partner to be found, preferably an experienced organization, will
assist in facilitating faster movement of goods from the port.
</P>
<P>
Observing that there have been widespread fears on the reported
 privatization of the port, Moi said the government can not sell
such a large and important organization.
</P>
<P>
Mombasa is not only a gateway to Kenya, but also to East and
Central Africa, he noted.
</P>
<P>
However, the president stressed the importance to commercialize
some operations, saying what Kenyans should do is to form a big
company to intensify and expand operations to regional countries
served by the port.
</P>
<P>
Mombasa port, the country's main sea outlet along the eastern
coast of the Indian Ocean, handles around 8.5 million tons of
cargo annually. The major users of the port include Uganda,
Rwanda and Burundi.  
</P>
</TEXT>
