<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Fiscal Deficit Up 28 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Indian fiscal deficit in
April-July (the first four months of the 1999-2000 fiscal year)
ballooned by over 28 percent to 543.54 billion Indian rupees
(12.64 billion U.S. dollars) against 423.00 billion rupees (9.84
billion dollars) in the same period in 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
According to the Financial Ministry, the government pegged the
fiscal deficit, including the small savings component, for
1999-2000 at 1,049.55 billion rupees (24.41 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
This was only marginally higher than the 1,037.37 billion
rupees (24.12 billion dollars) reported in the revised estimates
for 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
The government's total expenditure in the first four months of
the 1999-2000 fiscal year shot up nearly 16 percent to 902.32
billion rupees (20.98 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Net revenue receipts in the same period declined by 1 percent
to 336.95 billion rupees (7.84 billion dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
