<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Development Inalienable Human Right: Bangladeshi Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Development is an inalienable
human right, Bangladeshi Minister for Law, Justice and
Parliamentary Affairs Abdul Matin Khasru said in his keynote paper
to the Asian Parliamentarians' Conference for Peace and
Cooperation here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the rights proclaimed in the United Nations
Declaration on the Right to Development are meaningless for those
whose basic needs -- food, clothing, shelter, health care and
education are not fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
"The challenge before us has been to extend the noble ideals of
human rights relevant to those whose life is a constant desperate
struggle for survival at a sub-human level," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister called for appropriate economic measures and
mechanism for getting appropriate economic resources from
developed partners for the development of developing countries so
that the rights, particularly the economic, social and cultural
rights, guaranteed in the International Bill of Human Rights
become meaningful to the people in these countries.
</P>
<P>
Khasru stressed that Asia has different history, cultural and
social moorings, but at the same time Asia is connected and linked
by its strong belief in human dignity, respect for each other's
culture and religion. Asian civilization is based on the belief in
its roots and respect for its social values, struggle and
sacrifice of its ancestors for sustaining each of its
civilizations, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We, therefore, realize more than any other people and nation
as to how important it is to protect our freedom and sovereignty
to work for peace to ensure the sustainable development in our
region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Khasru noted that he will put forward to the conference, which
opened Wednesday, a proposal for setting in motion the process for
formulation and subsequent adoption of an "Asian Charter of Human
Rights."
</P>
<P>
Asia is the only major continent, which is yet to formulate its
own human rights instrument, he said, adding that the Asian
Parliamentarians' Conference For Peace and Cooperation may resolve
to become the appropriate forum for initiating the process for
formulation and adoption of the Asian Charter of Human Rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
