<HEADLINE> 66-Year-Old Man Donates Kidney To Help Save His Son </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Lu Qinghe, a 66-year-old man
in Zhengzhou, capital of central China's Henan Province, donated
one of his kidneys to his son on Wednesday in the first case in
China of a man of his age donating a kidney.
</P>
<P>
According to Chinese regulations, people above the age of 60
cannot donate a kidney because of possible cardiovascular or
cerebral complications during the operations. But Lu Qinghe's
anxiety and worry about his son's life made physicians decide to
have a try at it.
</P>
<P>
A physical examination before the operation helped urologists
at the Henan Provincial People's Hospital, that it was okay. Today,
both men are reported in good condition and the father's lungs,
heart, and cerebral system are all functioning well.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
