<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congolese Rebel Leader Optimistic of Lasting Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Rebel leader Ernest Wamba dia
Wamba of the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) said Wednesday
in Zimbabwean capital that he was optimistic lasting peace would
be achieved in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
"I believe Africa has enough experienced leaders interested in
making this continent peaceful in the likes of Julius Nyerere,
Robert Mugabe, Nelson Mandela and many others," a Zimbabwean
newspaper Thursday quoted him as saying at a public forum
organized by the Association of African Political Scientists.
</P>
<P>
"It is important that we all, including those that we fought
against, come together and give peace a chance. This is a time for
us to interact, exchange views and ways of ensuring that the
democratization of the Congo takes place for the good of the whole
continent. It is in this spirit of regional cooperation that we
find ourselves here," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wamba dia Wamba said that Africa has an obligation to make sure
that the Democratic Republic of the Congo achieves lasting
political stability on which regional peace would hinge.
</P>
<P>
"War has certain ways of educating us all. The moral of this
war in the DRC is that the needs, expectations and aspirations of
the majority have to be articulated through a national
government," he said.
</P>
<P>
He argued that unless African countries realized that it was
fundamental to have a majority and democratically elected
government which protected the interests of the minority,
stability would remain a dream, because it was this problem that
led to genocides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
