<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Unicom Stopping Joint Ventures Through Fair Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- China United
Telecommunications Corporation (China Unicom) will terminate its '
China-China-foreign' ventures through fair negotiations based on
state laws and regulations, according to Yang Xianzu, China Unicom
's chairman, today.
</P>
<P>
This does not mean terminating cooperation with foreign
partners, he said, but is meant to help create conditions for new
cooperation that comply with government regulations and to avoid
losses caused by delays.
</P>
<P>
Unicom is China's second largest telecoms operator and began
using the CCF method to finance projects by getting a Chinese
company to set up a joint venture with a foreign company. The
joint venture would then enter into a cooperation contract with
China Unicom and back the construction of telecoms infrastructure,
primarily GSM networks. After the completion of the project, the
parties involved would share the profits from the project in
agreed upon amounts.
</P>
<P>
Unicom has signed 46 such cooperative contracts with foreign
ventures, 43 of them for GSM and fixed line projects, involving
about a billion U.S. dollars worth of capital.
</P>
<P>
Yang says that because of CCF irregularities and the fact that
it does not comply with the relevant government policies and
regulations, the ventures have had numerous problems, and China
Unicom and many of its CCF partners have agreed that this is not
an ideal way to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, China Unicom began negotiating with foreign parties
for possibly terminating CCF ventures and reached an agreement
with some of them. On August 30 of this year, the Ministry of
Information Industries issued a statement saying that China Unicom
's CCF contracts with foreign businesses violated the current
government policies and regulations and needed to be corrected. It
asked China Unicom to study all the CCF ventures on a case-by-case
basis and to straighten them out by the end of September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Students Need More Physical Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey by the China
Children's Research Center, Beijing Normal University, and Beijing
Publishing House found that over 70 percent of China's primary and
secondary school students get less than 3 hours of exercise per
week, or less than half an hour each day.
</P>
<P>
The survey started last October among primary and secondary
school students aged 10 to 18 in 10 provinces and municipalities.
It found that as the years go by students have less time for
physical exercise and some secondary school students do almost
none.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 20 percent of the primary school students said that they
have no time for exercise outside of P.E. classes and nearly 34
percent of the junior high and 42 percent of the senior high
students said the same thing.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the survey reveals two problems: students
think that they have no need for physical exercise and the
pressure from studies causes them to give up exercise, and they
warn that these students need more exercise and a healthier
lifestyle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Economist for Int'l Currency Trading Regulations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 2 (Xinhua) -- There should be
international regulations for currency trading, a Japanese
economist said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"There should be some infrastructure surrounding currency
trading. There should be proper international regulations and a
more orderly state for currency trading," Eisuke Sakakibara,
special adviser to the minister of finance of Japan, said here at
the international symposium on currency controls and Asian
monetary cooperation.
</P>
<P>
However, he regretted that there does not seem to be any desire
to bring about transformation in the global financial
architecture.
</P>
<P>
Currency trading is zero sum game, Sakakibara, who is known as
"Mr. Yen", said, adding currency trading is very volatile but the
trading could not be prohibited in the new emerging
cyber-capitalistic system.
</P>
<P>
"We have overcome the immediate crisis but the root cause of
the problem is still with us, that is, the inherent instability of
cyber-capitalism and serious convulsions associated with the
transition," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said it was very important for all to recognize that the
world is passing through a period of great transformation and in
order to adapt to this great transformation, a shift in paradigm
is clearly necessary.
</P>
<P>
The shift in paradigm from market fundamentalism or the
perception that government and market are substitutes to a regime
where national governments and regional and international
organizations complement and interact with the market seems in
order, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
