<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rare Coin Brings 4 million Dollars at Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The famous Childs specimen
of the 1804 Silver Dollar has been sold for a world record 4.14
million U.S. dollars at a New York auction, a collectibles grading
company said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to Collector Universe, the U.S. largest provider of
collectibles grading and authentication services, the previous
rare coin world record was held by the Eliasberg specimen of the
1804 Silver Dollar that sold for 1.8 million dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Childs and Eliasberg specimens of the 1804 dollar are among
eight so-called "original" pieces believed to have been struck in
the mid-1930s for inclusion in presentation sets prepared as gifts
from the U.S. seventh president Andrew Jackson to rulers in the
Far Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Collector Universe said that the Childs specimen had not
appeared on the market for more than half a century. It last came
up for sale in 1945 when it was purchased for 5,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
In purchasing the coin in 1945, businessman Charles Childs was
expanding a collection beginning in 1870 by his grandfather,
Walter Childs. For a period of several decades in the 1800s and
early 1900s, Walter Childs bought proof coins each year from the
Philadelphia Mint. All of these coins remained in the family
collection through succeeding generations before being consigned
to the New York auction Monday.
</P>
<P>
In all the Childs sales included 803 lots and realized a total
of more than nine million dollars, according to Collector Universe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
