<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Fires Rockets into Northern Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's leading anti-Israeli
group Hezbollah Wednesday night fired Katyusha rockets into
northern Israel to avenge the killing of two Lebanese civilians by
Israeli shelling.
</P>
<P>
About 25 rockets were fired into Kiryat Shemona in northern
Israel. There has been no reports about the casualties.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah's attack came after two Lebanese civilians were
killed in the Israeli shelling on the Labbaya village in the
country's western Bekka Valley on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Another five villagers were wounded in the bombardment.
</P>
<P>
Israel's offensive was triggered by a roadside bomb detonated
by Hezbollah near the village which killed at least five members
of the pro-Israeli South Lebanon Army (SLA).
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been
spearheading a guerrilla war to oust Israeli troops and their
allied SLA out of the country.
</P>
<P>
In June, Israeli warplanes heavily bombed Lebanon's
infrastructure and killed nine people after Hezbollah launched
Katyusha rockets into its north.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's two power plants and three key coastal bridges that
were destroyed in the June attack are still under repair and
residents in the capital and its environs have been suffering from
lack of electricity supply. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
