<HEADLINE> Rescue Teams Rushing to Plane Crash Scene in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. embassy staff and
Tanzanian officials are heading toward the scene where a plane
carrying ten U.S. tourists crashed, but reports about casualties
of the incident are not available at the moment.
</P>
<P>
Director of the United States Information Service in Tanzania,
Dudley Sims, told Xinhua Thursday morning that two persons from
the embassy have almost reached the scene, and will keep informing
progress of the rescue job hour in hour.
</P>
<P>
"They telephoned us at six this morning, saying that they are
half an hour (drive) from the scene. By now, they haven't ringed
us," he said.
</P>
<P>
Another rescue group sent by U.S. embassy in Nairobi, Kenya,
is also rushing to the scene, Sims said.
</P>
<P>
The small charter plane was carrying the tourists from the
world-famous Serengeti National Park to the Kilimanjaro Airport in
northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
On board the Cessna aircraft, which went down some 12 miles
away from the 14,979-foot Mount Meru, the fifth highest in Africa,
also included a Tanzanian tour guide and a pilot.
</P>
<P>
Mount Meru, often surrounded by cloud, is a part of the Arusha
National Park located some 45 kilometers from the Arusha town in
the Arusha Region.
</P>
<P>
The Arusha Regional Commissioner, Daniel ole Njoolay, told
Xinhua that so far he has scanty information about the incident
but will keep following it.
</P>
<P>
The tourists included three couples and a group of four that
came from Florida, Massachusetts, Connecticut, California and New
Jersey, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Rescue efforts involving helicopters have started since
Wednesday after the plane crashed at around 10:20 a.m. local time
(0720GMT) but were hampered by foggy weather.
</P>
<P>
The Serengeti park draws tens of thousands of tourists every
year for its wide range of big game animals and the annual
migration of millions of wildlife.
</P>
<P>
Acting permanent secretary in the Ministry of Natural Resources
and Tourism R. P. Kabende left Tanzanian capital Thursday morning
for Arusha to handle issues related to the incident, said an
official with the ministry.
</P>
</TEXT>
