<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi Thursday urged Malaysian and
foreign-owned information technology (IT) companies to form
strategic alliances and joint ventures for mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
"Sharing does not diminish competitiveness. In fact, it brings
together resources, which combined, can effectively progress and
prosper for mutual benefit," Abdullah said when launching WebHost
Asia at Cyberjaya near here.
</P>
<P>
He said his government has given its full support for the
development and growth of the IT industry in Malaysia by investing
in technology and infrastructure, and hoped that IT entrepreneurs
would focus on developing the industry from the ground-up by
taking advantage of the infrastructure provided.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to see more local IT companies embarking on such
bold and innovative ventures and, at the same time, sharing their
technology with both local and foreign firms to enhance Malaysia's
role in the global digital revolution," he said.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said the Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC), a
50-kilometer by 15-kilometer zone stretching southwards from here
designated as a hub for the development of multimedia products and
services, offered unlimited opportunities for those willing to
work hard and use the opportunities.
</P>
<P>
He said the positive 4.1 percent growth of gross domestic
product (GDP) for the second quarter signaled that the worst was
over for Malaysia. "It also signifies that with renewed growth,
there will be more opportunities especially in the fast-growing
and ever-changing industry like IT in areas like e-commerce," he
said. 
