<HEADLINE> Kenya to Record 13,000 Road Deaths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenya may lose about 13,000
lives through road accidents by the end of this year, Health
Minister Jackson Kalweo has said.
</P>
<P>
It will be the highest death toll recorded in a single year
and will surpass the average annual rate of 2,000 deaths
registered since the late 1980s, the East African Standard
Thursday quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a nine-day course on " Spot Advanced Life Support"
held recently in the country's capital Nairobi, Kalweo disclosed
that 6,000 Kenyans had died from road accidents in the first seven
months of this year.
</P>
<P>
The minister observed that 35 percent of those killed on road
were people aged between 15 and 45.
</P>
<P>
To counter the threat posed by various disasters, Kalweo said,
his ministry had placed various strategic interventions in the
National Health Sector Strategic Plan, covering the 1999-2004
period.  
</P>
