<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inaugural Meeting to Launch EALAF Opens in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 2 (Xinhua) -- More than 100 officials from
27 East Asian and Latin American countries including China began
their two-day discussions Thursday to lay groundwork for the East
Asia-Latin America Forum (EALAF) mooted by Singapore Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony, Singapore Minister for
Foreign Affairs and Law S. Jayakkumar said the forum is not "a
talk shop" and asked participants to share some of the broad
ideas that lie behind the thinking of this new forum.
</P>
<P>
Listing the linkages built between different regions in the
world, such as Asian-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC), the deep
trans-Atlantic links between Europe and North America, the
Organization of American States (OAS) and the Free Trade Area of
the Americas (FTAA) and the Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM) as well as
historical and other links between Europe and Latin America,
Jayakumar said the missing link is between East Asia and Latin
America and the gap prevents both regions from mutually exploiting
their enormous economic potential.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that the forum is neither just about geography and
nor only about trade and economic, Jayakumar said "the lack of
understanding about regions that are, in reality, no longer far
flung created a latent instability in the international system."
</P>
<P>
"The lack of systematic historical contacts does give a certain
intrinsic value to dialogue to build greater common
understanding," he added.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out the post Cold War world has seen two
contradictory trends, adding that "the ever closer integration of
the global economy has not created greater international
cohesion."
</P>
<P>
"On the contrary, globalisation has meant an ever greater
disconnect between economic geography, political geography,
financial geography and social and cultural geography," he added.
</P>
<P>
He made clear the project will be making progress step by step
and next year will see the convening of a meeting of foreign
ministers of the forum.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony on behalf of Latin America countries,
Ambassador Cristial Barros, head of the Chile delegation, said
Latin America expects to foster closer links with East Asia
countries.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his wish that "the forum will operates with full
independence from other existing intraregional or inter-regional
organization" and build a forum "whose nature is unique, where the
countries participate independently and not under the scheme of
regional blocs."
</P>
<P>
The project of the forum was first proposed by Singapore Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong during his visit to Chile in October 1998
and he conceived the forum as a multi-dimensional dialogue to help
break down barriers and encourage the evolution of more concrete
links between East Asia and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
However, the prime minister had said the potential of linking
the two regions is likely to take 10 years or more due to the lack
of historic contact, awareness and understanding between both
regions and the launch of the forum will thus be the start of a
long-term process to bring that synergy to fruition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
