<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Favors Proposed Asian Regional Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand Thursday
responded favorably to Japan's proposal to set up an Asian
Regional Fund.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi Thursday
described it as a working mechanism that can be acceptable to all
as well as functional in the context of the prevailing financial
market.
</P>
<P>
Although the proposal was shot down by the United States,
certain Asian countries seemed to be showing some favorable
response towards it, he said at the international symposium on
currency controls and Asian monetary cooperation here. His speech
was delivered by Sura Sanittanont, special advisor to the minister
of commerce of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
"Sentiment towards such supplementary and complementary
arrangements have since become more accommodating," he said,
adding "this is evident by the fact that the Miyazawa fund of 30
billion U.S. dollars to assist affected countries was acceptable
to the United States, the International Monetary Fund and the
World Bank."
</P>
<P>
Suggesting a case be made for the creation of a financial
safety net for the weaker and open economies in the Asia Pacific
region, Supachai said this would help these economies cope with
possible future financial crisis even when the United States is
unsure that IMF resources will be sufficient to deal with another
crisis of a similar magnitude.
</P>
<P>
He said the still unrecovered economies in Asia are not
equipped to deal with the volatility, uncertainty and disruptions
in the world financial market, and all these could cause another
financial crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
