<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Set Up Kosovo Relief Aid Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia is considering
setting up a center to coordinate medical relief aid and missions
to help Kosovo war victims.
</P>
<P>
The proposed center would, among other things, coordinate
deployment of medical volunteers to help Kosovo recover from
prolonged ethnic conflicts, Bernama news agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The government is taking the initiative following feedback from
Malaysian medical teams whose Kosovo relief efforts were arranged
by a United States-based volunteer organization, Foreign Minister
Syed Hamid Albar said in the northern state of Kedah Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
"From the feedback we reckon that Kosovo is in dire need of
medical aid and the government, on its part, feels that it needs
to coordinate these voluntary medical missions," Syed Hamid was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said his ministry was studying the financial and other
implications of setting up such a center before making a
commitment.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, several other countries already have
such coordination centers run by non-government organizations and
governments.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the minister said that donations for the Kosovo
Action Fund by Malaysians and the government now totaling 4
million ringgit (over 1 million U.S. dollars) would be handed
over to Kosovo leaders soon for rebuilding and repairing damaged
schools and mosques. 
</P>
</TEXT>
