<HEADLINE> Polish Deputy Prime Minister Dismissed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Polish Prime Minister Jerzy
Buzek Wednesday night announced that Janusz Tomaszewski was
removed from his posts as deputy Prime Minister and the Minister
of Internal Affairs and Administration.
</P>
<P>
Buzek did not appoint a successor, nor gave reasons for the
dismissal. Tomaszewski was the second minister removed from his
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
According to Polish Press Agency reports, Buzek called in
Tomaszewski in the evening to tell him that he was no longer
trusted and his assistance no longer needed.
</P>
<P>
Some people believed Tomaszewski was fired for his improper
reaction to whether he should receive a court investigation or not.
</P>
<P>
Tomaszewski, a former automobile mechanic and the vice-chairman
of the Solidarity Trade Union, took his office on October 31, 1996
when Buzek set up his cabinet. Since then, he had provoked much
criticism over his leadership, which some people said had led to "
chaos" in his ministry and a "terrible state of public security."
</P>
<P>
The polish political circle gave mixed reactions to his
dismissal. Some considered the move as "another government crisis",
while others proposed an institutional reform to divide the
current Ministry of Internal Affairs and Administration into two
parts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
