<HEADLINE> India's Exports Up 4.04 percent in April-July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- India's exports stood at
11.041 billion U.S. dollars in April-July, an increase of 4.04
percent over 10.61 billion U.S dollars recorded a year ago.
</P>
<P>
According to the provisional foreign trade data released by the
Commerce Ministry, in rupee terms, the exports grew by 8.45
percent during this period.
</P>
<P>
Exports in July only reached 3.05 billion U.S. dollars, a 2.11
percent rise as against 2.99 billion U.S. dollars during the same
month last year.
</P>
<P>
The months of May and June witnessed exports notching up a
growth of 11.68 percent and 11.14 percent over the corresponding
months in 1998-1999.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the rupee is overvalued, which handicaps
exports of the country's products. 
</P>
