<HEADLINE> Milosevic Promises Release of Two Australians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 1 (Xinhua)-- Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic promised on Wednesday to free two Australians who were
arrested for espionage during the NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from Tanjug News Agency, Milosevic made
this promise at a meeting with a delegation of Serbian Australian
emigrants. The president said that in return for the great support
from 300,000 Serbian emigrants during NATO airstrikes, Yugoslavia
decided to accept the request by the delegation to release the two
Australians -- Prat and Valas.
</P>
<P>
The security organ of Yugoslavia destroyed the spy network
under the leadership of Prat this April. Yugoslavia accused them
of spying under the name of humanitarianism organization "Care
International".
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia arrested them on charges of collecting information
about the movement of Yugoslav police and troops and about the
bombing effects before and during the attacks. Australia has
demanded several times the release of Prat and Valas, but all
requests have been rejected by Yugoslavia. 
</P>
