<HEADLINE> Singapore Provides Computers to Nepali Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A Singaporean community club
will provide 100 computers and accessories worth 36,550 U.S.
dollars to various public schools in Nepal, The Kathmandu Post
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Bouna Vista Community Club of
Singapore reached an agreement with the National Planning
Commission (NPC) of Nepal Wednesday to provide computers and
computer teachers training to Nepal under the project named
Initiate Nepal.
</P>
<P>
The project aims at promoting and developing Information
Technology in Nepal. The club has already dispatched a team of 15
computer education experts to Nepal.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, 30 computers will be used for the
Computer Teachers Training Center to be operated in the Ministry
of Science and Technology and about 60 computers will be
distributed to various schools of the country. The rest will be
used for management and monitoring purposes in NPC and the
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
In order to develop the information technology and match the
growth in the world, the Nepalese government has formulated a
three-way plan, including software development, human resources
development and the establishment of an information technology
park. 
