<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Children Begin First School Year After NATO Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav pupils and middle
school students on Wednesday began their first school year after
NATO's 78-day-long airstrike.
</P>
<P>
Around 900,000 pupils of over 1,700 primary schools and 350,000
students of 650 middle schools attended school on September 1 in
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
Serbian Minister of Education, Jovo Todorovich, attended an
opening ceremony of a primary school in Belgrade. He said this
school had been bombed by NATO, but the Education Ministry managed
to repair it before the term began.
</P>
<P>
On March 24, NATO started the airstrike on Yugoslavia. Yugoslav
children were deprived of education during the bombing, and many
school buildings were damaged. The Education Ministry appropriated
33 million dinar (about 3 million U.S. dollars) for reparing them.
</P>
</TEXT>
