<HEADLINE> Pyongyang Declares Maritime Military Control Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The General Staff
Headquarters of the Korean People's Army (KPA) declared its
maritime military control zone off western Korea on Thursday, one
day after Pyongyang and Washington failed to agree on demarcating
a maritime boundary, the Korean Central News Agency (KCNA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
The KPA at the same time declared as invalid the "plunderous"
Northern Limit Line, which was unilaterally drawn by the United
States at the end of the Korean War in 1953 and which was never
recognized by the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
It stressed that the DPRK would exercise its self-defense right
over the military boundary on the sea "by various means and
methods."
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, DPRK and U.S. negotiators failed to reach any
agreement in the sixth round of general-level talks since the
naval forces from the Republic of Korea (ROK) and DPRK exchanged
gun fire off the Korean Peninsula's west coast on June 15.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK government ruled out further general-level talks with
the United States on the maritime boundary issue, condemning the U.
S. for lacking the necessary sincerity in solving the boundary
dispute between the north and south. 
</P>
</TEXT>
