<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Build Six New Fishery Harbors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government will
build six new fishery harbors next year in a bid to meet the
challenges of the fishing industry in the next millennium,
officials here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The proposed six fishery harbors will be located in Chilaw,
Hambantota, Ambalangoda, Kalametiya, Dikowita and Dodanduwa. The
blueprints of these projects at present are being prepared while
feasibility studies on some are being conducted, Fisheries and
Aquatic Resources Development Minister Mahinda Rajapakse said.
</P>
<P>
Of the six harbors, four will be constructed under an Asian
Development Bank-funded aid program while the Dikowita harbor will
be funded by the Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund in Japan.
</P>
<P>
The fifth one, Dodanduwa harbor which is estimated to cost 2.5
million U.S. dollars will be totally funded by the Sri Lankan
government, the sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
