<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Favors Free Market Without Currency Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said Thursday Malaysia is not disloyal to free
market if currency trading is disallowed.
</P>
<P>
The free market can still function without currency trading and
without adverse effects on real trade and foreign investments
flowing into productive sectors, he said at a symposium here on
the first anniversary of the capital controls imposed by Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The symposium is being attended by some 500 participants
including Eisuke Sakakibara, special adviser to the finance
minister of Japan, Amar Bhattacharya, senior adviser to the World
Bank and Heiner Flassbeck, former vice-finance minister of
Germany.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that for a long time, there was no currency
trading while world trade grew economically and fixed exchange
rates enabled values to be attached to goods and services.
</P>
<P>
"We in Malaysia feel that we are not disloyal to the free
market if we disallow currency trading. Our real trade should not
be affected nor should foreign investment in productive capacities
suffer," Mahathir said in his keynote address focusing on why
Malaysia's selective currency controls are necessary and why they
have worked.
</P>
<P>
He said selective capital controls were successful because they
were a soft system, as Managing Director of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) Michel Camdessus had said.
</P>
<P>
Another reason why Malaysia was very successful was because of
its export drive whereby foreign exchange came in by the buckets,
Mahathir said. "There was no shortage of foreign exchange and
there was no liquidity problem."
</P>
<P>
A third reason for the success is the fact that Malaysia is
very sincerely trying to guarantee the stability of the Malaysian
ringgit, not its value, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We wanted a fixed rate, not a high rate for the ringgit. For
Malaysia, it succeeded because it sought to stabilize the ringgit
at a reasonable level, not at an overvalued level for technical
stabilization reasons and because Malaysia always had its exports
and national competitiveness at the forefront," he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia pegged the ringgit to the U.S. dollar at a rate of
3.80 in early September last year among the selective capital
controls.
</P>
<P>
"Another reason was that "with this single bold step,
confidence in the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE), the ringgit
and in the real economy was quickly restored," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Without this rapid, almost overnight restoration of
confidence, we could not have succeeded," he added.
</P>
<P>
To be sure, some external factors helped a great deal, Mahathir
said, adding that the currency stabilization in East Asia and the
economic recovery in East Asian economies have been a great help.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that Malaysia has been able to achieve what
others have achieved without having to go into massive debts,
without saddling future generations with massive debt servicing
burdens, without having to sell family silver and precious
heirlooms, without having to auction off precious corporations to
foreigners with fire-sale prices, without having to bend and bow
to anyone and without having to kiss anyone's feet.
</P>
<P>
He said that the economies of East Asia are all different, so
comparisons are often difficult and unfair.
</P>
<P>
"But most surely, each country has the right to decide on its
priorities and to choose its own path to recovery. And most
obviously, the unorthodox, bold and strong measures which we took
366 days ago have borne fruit," Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is well on the road to recovery as the economy
recorded a 4.1-percent gross domestic product growth in the
second quarter this year after a contraction of five consecutive
quarters.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian economy, hit by the Asian financial crisis since
July 1997, had a negative growth of 6.7 percent in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Export Grows by 14 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Total merchandise export of the
Philippines amounted to 2.851 billion U.S. dollars in July, 14
percent higher than last year's 2.501 billion dollars, a report of
the National Statistics Office said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, total export receipts for the period
of January to July 1999 grew by 13.7 percent to 18.654 billion
dollars from 16.406 billion dollars recorded during the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
For July alone, electronics and components, accounting for 53.4
percent of the aggregate receipts, valued at 1.522 billion
dollars, 27.5 percent higher than the 1.194 billion dollars of
July 1998.
</P>
<P>
Input/output peripheral units emerged as the country's second
biggest earner for the month with sales amounting to 236.87
million dollars, an increase of 32.3 percent over 1998's 178.99
million dollars, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Manufactured goods netted 2.603 billion dollars in July, up
from 2.193 billion dollars a year earlier, posting an 18.7-percent
upswing in receipts and accounting for 91.3 percent of the
aggregate earning.
</P>
<P>
Agro-based products ranked second among the country's major
export groups and accounted for 4.2 percent of the total
dollar-inflow for the month even as sales fell by 32.1 percent to
119.45 million dollars from 175.81 million dollars the same month
last year.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that exports to the United States grew by 6.6
percent to 992.74 million dollars from 931.57 million dollars a
year earlier and accounted for 34.8 percent of the total receipts.
</P>
<P>
Japan remained at the second spot with a 13.7-percent share.
Sales to Japan rose by 9.0 percent to 391.55 million dollars from
359.24 million dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Other major markets for July 1999 were Singapore, the
Netherlands, Taiwan, Britain, Hong Kong, Germany, Malaysia and
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Total earnings from the top 10 markets amounted to 2.55 billion
dollars or 89.3 percent of the total, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
