<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Strong Yen, Good or Bad for Asia? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese yen has been
climbing to new highs against the U.S. dollar during recent
trading sessions, but the potential effects of a strong yen on
Asian economies are yet to be felt.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Japanese yen maintained its 109 level against
the greenback in trading, still the highest in seven months.
</P>
<P>
But the continuous rise of the yen in the past week has failed
to lift Asian currencies much, as the regional markets were
dragged down by the U.S. Federal Reserve System's move to raise
U.S. interest rates on August 24.
</P>
<P>
As Japan is other Asian nations' major trade partner, the yen's
rebound is crucial to the region's economic comeback. A year ago,
when the Japanese yen started to surge again after falling beyond
140 to the dollar, its rally supported Asian currencies and
allowed the crisis-stricken nations to cut interest rates.
</P>
<P>
But now, Asia's economic recovery is already on track and the
yen's appreciation does not have the same effect on Asian
currencies as it did a year ago. To maintain their export
competitiveness, Asian countries would rather keep their
currencies relatively weak.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, the peso declined to 39.87 to the dollar
last week, a 10-month low, after the central bank cut its key
policy rates 20 times earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the Central Bank of the Philippines did not
intervene. Instead, Central Bank Governor Rafael Buenaventura said
that his bank would be comfortable with an exchange rate between
38.50 and 38.90 pesos against the dollar this year.
</P>
<P>
Just like the Philippines, other Asian countries do want to
take advantage of relatively weak currencies to stimulate export
growth.
</P>
<P>
In South Korea, the authorities are expected to prevent any
significant appreciation of the won, which was trading around
1,180 to the dollar recently.
</P>
<P>
"For South Korea, which is coming out of a very very deep
recession, maintaining a stable inflation, interest rate and
exchange rate environment is clearly conducive to producing a
sustainable economic recovery," said Duncan Woolridge, senior
economist at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
For such purposes, Asian countries would like to see a strong
yen, because the yen's up trend will give them a competitive edge
over Japan in the global export market, and increase Japan's
demand for export products from other Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
"The yen's strength is clearly positive for Asian exports. You
are starting to see the effects coming through now. Asian exports
to Japan are picking up strongly," said Rob Subbaraman, an
economist at Lehman Brothers in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, economists said, a strong yen would benefit
Asia with more Japanese investments in the region, where countries
are badly in need of more foreign investments to speed up the
recovery process.
</P>
<P>
But in the long run, the strong yen, which would cause a
slowdown in the Japanese recovery, will hurt Asian economies. The
steady surge in the yen has already started eating into profits of
Japan's biggest companies and threatens to hold back the chances
of a swift economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that if the yen averages at 113 to the dollar or
higher in the fiscal year ending next march then there will be no
growth in corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
When the Japanese economy begins to slow down because of the
strong yen, it will affect Japan's domestic demand for Asian
products, and Asian economies will then be hurt, they said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the strong yen is good for Asia only in the short
term, but bad for the region in the longer term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
