<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oldest Roman Catholic Church in Asia Discovered Near Silk Road (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A 700-year-old church site
discovered on a route to the old Silk Road is believed to be the
site of the earliest Roman Catholic church in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The church was located in a town known as Abinsm, meaning "a
place with many temples" in Mongol, about 190 kilometers north of
the city of Baotou in the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region. The
remaining walls are about five meters high. There was believed to
be a 100-square-meter main hall with two rostrums four to five
meters high at one end.
</P>
<P>
Shattered around are quite a lot of white glazed tiles and
other tiles with decorations that were popular in Ancient Rome.
Chinese archeologists had been hesitant to reach a conclusion
about the church's origins until recently when they found a white
stone lion under the ruins. The 16-centimeter lion does not
resemble traditional Chinese stone lions and is more like those in
front of Catholic churches in Italy.
</P>
<P>
This is enough to show that this church's origins are similar
to those of Catholic churches in the West, according to
archeologist Gai Shanlin in Inner Mongolia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
