<HEADLINE> Nokia, Reuters Team up to Develop News Services on Mobile Phones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Nokia and Reuters have signed
a global cooperation agreement to develop and deliver financial,
sports and general news services based on the Wireless Application
Protocol (WAP).
</P>
<P>
The news services are optimized for Nokia 7110, the world's
first mobile phone for Internet access launched early this year.
</P>
<P>
The services have been developed to work with the Nokia
Messaging Platform and are currently available to operators
participating in Nokia WAP pilots.
</P>
<P>
With the WAP system making bitmap imaging possible, the Reuters
logo, featured as a wireless bitmap, will appear on the phone
display when it enters the service.
</P>
<P>
"The delivery of Reuters news and information services via WAP-
based phones is a strategic objective of ours," said Jonathan
Bailem, managing director of Reuters Wireless Services.
</P>
<P>
"Combined with Reuters' position as a global source of content
delivery, Nokia enables the mobile information society, bringing
news to everyone's pocket," said Pekka Salonoja, vice President of
Nokia Wireless Data Server Systems.
</P>
<P>
"Nokia now has over 20 WAP pilots worldwide with innovative
operators. Reuters news services are an important addition to the
services currently offered," he added.
</P>
<P>
The WAP standard includes a wide range of value-added services
for mobile phones, such as Internet access and data and images
transmitting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
