<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New WTO Chief Pledges to Facilitate China's Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The new director-general of the
World Trade Organization (WTO), Mike Moore, pledged here Wednesday
to do what he can to help China join the world trading bloc as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
China, as a world power, has to sit at the table one day, Moore
told reporters, adding,"I'll do anything I can to facilitate China
's membership."
</P>
<P>
China has negotiated for 13 years with WTO members on
conditions for its accession to the WTO.
</P>
<P>
Moore also promised to help the poorest countries when he
officially took office earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
"The very poor, the (48) least-developed countries, still don't
get the access they need for their products and the technical
assistance to fully engage, so that they can sit at the table of
our global family and share equally and fully," the former New
Zealand prime minister said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The new WTO chief called on the richer countries to play their
part by opening their own markets to goods from poorer regions,
saying "it would not cost rich nations much to wipe away barriers
for the poorest countries."
</P>
<P>
Moore said that addressing the plight of the poorest members
had to be a key element of the agenda for the WTO's third
Ministerial Conference in the U.S. west coast city of Seattle
scheduled for November 30 to December 3.
</P>
<P>
Moore and Supachai Panitchpakdi of Thailand were chosen as the
WTO's next two consecutive leaders by the ruling General Council
on July 22.
</P>
<P>
Moore will head the WTO until August 31, 2002 when he will be
replaced by Supachai who will also serve a three-year term until
August 31, 2005.
</P>
<P>
At the decision-making meeting on July 22, WTO members agreed
that neither should be eligible for re-appointment as WTO chief,
nor should the period of office be extended.
</P>
<P>
Normally, the term of office of the WTO chief is four years as
former WTO Director-General Renato Ruggiero had served.
</P>
<P>
The decision was a compromise based on proposals by Bangladesh
and Australia after a year-long dispute among WTO members on who
would succeed Ruggiero. Ruggiero left office as scheduled on April
30, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
