<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- President Jiang Zemin told Chinese police force yesterday
that "maintaining stability is the overwhelming priority."
</P>
<P>
Jiang, who is also chairman of the Central Military Commission,
praised the police force for their proven reliability in the
ongoing struggle of maintaining social security. And he encouraged
them to make continued efforts to create favorable conditions for
reform and development.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks during a ceremony to highlight police work,
where he met model police officers and relatives of those who have
sacrificed their lives in the course of their duties.
</P>
<P>
-- Hu Jintao, member of the Standing Committee of the Political
Bureau of the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee,
said yesterday that educating party officials in line with the
requirements of the "three stresses" must be carried out to the
letter.
</P>
<P>
Hu made the remarks while attending the opening ceremony of a
new semester of the Party School of the CPC Central Committee, of
which he is also president.
</P>
<P>
The "three stresses" involves underlining and strengthening
theoretical study, political awareness, and good conduct.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin accepted credentials of four
newly-appointed ambassadors to China at the Great Hall of the
People yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The four ambassadors are Rajab Mohammed Sukayri of Jordan,
Cecilio Garza Limon of Mexico, Bayer Mihaly of Hungary and Lefa
Joseph Mokotj of Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
-- Xinhua News Agency released a commentary yesterday
denouncing Lee Teng-hui for inserting his "two states" remarks
into a resolution of the Kuomintang held on August 28-29.
</P>
<P>
The commentary says that under Lee's control, the "2nd plenary
session of the Kuomintang's 15th Congress" passed the resolution
to "set the tone" of the cross-Straits relations.
</P>
<P>
His move of including the "two states" remarks into party
resolution exposed his political malice and naivety as well as his
intention to split Chinese territorial integrity and sovereignty
and an attempt to separate Taiwan from China, the commentary says.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Australian Prime Minister John Howard said Chinese President
Jiang Zemin's forthcoming state visit to Australia will
significantly advance bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with Xinhua, Howard described the visit
as "a very significant event" and "a huge boost to the
relationship between Australia and China".
</P>
<P>
In Bangkok, Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai told Xinhua Jiang
's visit to Thailand will be a historical landmark for bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
-- People from different walks of life offered a mix of
reactions to the revision to the Personal Income Tax Law, which
allows the government to levy tax on interests earned from savings
deposits.
</P>
<P>
The Standing Committee of the Ninth National People's Congress
passed an amendment to the law on Monday. The amendment is
expected to reduce the incentive to save and lessen the banks'
burden of having to pay out large sums of accumulated interest,
according to lawmakers.  
