<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Woman Dedicated to Weather Forecasting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Editor's note: This year marks the 50th anniversary of the
founding of the People's Republic of China (PRC). Xinhua News
Agency is releasing a series of stories about 50 Chinese men and
women, young and old, who will describe their own experiences and
how they fit into the changes that have taken place in the past
five decades in China. This is the 12th story.
</P>
<P>
LHASA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Travelers who fly to Tibet must
have noticed that all the landings and take-offs at Lhasa airport,
the capital of the autonomous region, are carried out in the early
hours of the morning.
</P>
<P>
This is because of the turbulent and changing climate on this
mountainous plateau which has an average altitude of more than 4,
000 meters.
</P>
<P>
Weather forecasting, therefore, is seen as one of the most
difficult and challenging jobs in Tibet. That's why Pubu Zhuoma, a
47-year old ethnic Tibetan woman, has become such a celebrity
figure for the local people.
</P>
<P>
Zhuoma is one of the first Tibetan women working in this field
and moreover, she is the first Tibetan weather forecaster who has
gained national recognition thanks to her own efforts.
</P>
<P>
In 1969, Zhuoma first had a taste of fame for being good at
studying the works of the late Chinese leader Mao Zedong. One year
later, she left the countryside, where she labored as a "re-
educated youth", like many of her contemporaries, and was assigned
to work in the regional meteorological bureau as a telegraphist.
</P>
<P>
Shortly afterwards, she began to learn the skill of weather
forecasting from experts and even local herders who have an innate
understanding of climatic changes. And the girl was so involved in
this meteorological work that she had turned down several
invitations to study other subjects in university.
</P>
<P>
In 1974, Zhuoma's dream came true when she was admitted to
Yunnan University to study her beloved subject. Three years later,
she returned to the regional meteorological bureau to work as a
weather forecaster.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Zhuoma has devoted almost all her time to the work
and given little care to her family. "In recent years, I have
always thought I must pay greater attention to family life," she
said, "but I can't."
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, this unusual and talented Tibetan woman
has published a number of academic papers examining Tibet's
temperamental climate, especially focusing on catastrophic snow
and rain storms.
</P>
<P>
Now, she is acclaimed as one of the most successful
meteorologists in Tibet while one of her main works, "The Annual
Calendar of Meteorological Forecasts For Farmers", is being read
by many local weathermen, agricultural workers and herdsmen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0333 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hingis Breezes into Third Round at U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 1 (Xinhua) -- One day after the men's side
of the U.S. Open was rocked by the exit of Pete Sampras and
Patrick Rafter, top seed Martina Hingis of Switzerland left little
room for drama on the women's end.
</P>
<P>
Hingis breezed into the third round with a 6-1, 6-1 win over
Sarah Pitkowski of France today at the $14.5 million grand slam
event here.
</P>
<P>
World No. 1 Sampras and two-time defending champion Rafter were
forced to withdraw rom the tournament Tuesday with injuries,
leaving the top half of the men's draw wide open. Meanwhile, the
women's draw has been more true to form with 15 of the 16 seeded
players still alive.
</P>
<P>
The 19-year-old Hingis needed just 46 minutes to dismiss
Pitkowski, and was grateful to have such an easy second-round
match.
</P>
<P>
"I prefer it once in a while. It's nice," Hingis said. "Because
the other tournaments are tough. All the best players are there,
you have to take every single round seriously. But here at a Grand
Slam, till you get in the better rounds, it's nice to have a match
like that."
</P>
<P>
Third-seed Venus Williams of the United States attempts to stay
on course for a possible semifinal meeting with Hingis when she
faces Anne-Galle Sidot of France tonight.
</P>
<P>
Williams, regarded as one of the favorites to win her first
Grand Slam singles title, crushed Belarussian qualifier Tatiana
Poutchek 6-1, 6-2 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Also advancing today were 10th seed and 1994 champion Arantxa
Sanchez-Vicario of Spain, who easily defeated Nicole Pratt of
Australia 6-2, 6-2; 12th seed Barbara Schett of Austria, who
downed Sweden's Asa Carlsson 6-4, 6-2; No. 13 Dominique Van Roost
of Belgium beat Italy's Rita Grande 6-3, 6-3; and 15th seed Amelie
Mauresmo of France downed South African Mariaan De Swardt 4-6, 6-1,
6-3.
</P>
<P>
In the other second-round match involving seeded women, No. 8
Jana Novotna of the Czech Republic connected on just 39 percent of
her first serves but still was able to dispose of Slovenia's Tina
Krizian 6-0, 6-3 in one hour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
