<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0335 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museum of Overpasses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Beijing has been turned into a
virtual museum of overpasses, with some 200 now in the metropolis
following the completion of several modern ones in advance of the
country's National Day which falls on October 1.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's flyovers are plentiful, large, of high quality, and
come in a variety of shapes, some cloverleafs, some round, and
others of a rhombus design.
</P>
<P>
The new flyovers newly built or reconstructed this year include
the four-layer "Sihui Bridge" with an area of 110,000 square
meters in east Beijing, and the rainbow-like Dabeiyao junction
leading to the embassy compound.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's first three overpasses, the Baifu, the Balizhuang,
and the Chedaogou, were completed in 1966. And the cloverleaf at
Fuxingmen junction, the first one in Beijing, was open to traffic
in 1974, while the three-layer Jianguomen overpass, the first with
separate lanes for bikes and autos, was completed in 1979.
</P>
<P>
The late 1980s and early 1990s saw the rapid growth of
overpasses, when the 33-km-long Second Ring Road and the 48-km-
long Third Ring Road were built to ease traffic congestion in
downtown Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"Overpasses have helped form a traffic system combining public
and cargo vehicles and railways, " said Zhang Ren, deputy chief
engineer with the Beijing Municipal Design and Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhang, the number of automobiles has climbed to
more than 1.3 million now, compared with 400,000 a decade ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0336 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
