<HEADLINE> Relatives Gathering in Memory of Swissair Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- People are gathering in memory
of Swissair victims Wednesday in Canada's easternmost province of
Nova Scocia.
</P>
<P>
Among the solemn mourners are 650 relatives of the victims who
carry wreaths and bouquets to an interment site overlooking the
scene of the disaster.
</P>
<P>
A total of 227 people died in the crash of Swissair Flight 111
in the waters of St. Margarets's Bay on September 2, 1998.
</P>
<P>
About two dozens ground searchers who helped find human remains
a year ago formed a guard of honor at the start of the private
memorial ceremony, local media reported.
</P>
<P>
At the site, three tall columns have been erected to symbolize
the numeral 111, the Swissair flight number.
</P>
<P>
Another memorial is planned for later in the day at Whalesback,
where families are to meet workers and volunteers who helped in
search and recovery efforts, media said.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien will also
attend a commemorative gathering in the provincial capital
Halifax, the media added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
