<HEADLINE> British Soldiers on Drunken Rampage in Italy's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The mayor of Sorrento, the famous
resort on Italy's south coast, has ordered a two-day ban on
alcohol sales after 400 drunken British soldiers caused havoc in
the town Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Two of the soldiers, on leave after a six-month stint in
Kosovo, stole a car and hurtled around Sorrento's quaint streets,
injuring two residents before they were caught and arrested by
police.
</P>
<P>
About 1,000 British soldiers aboard four ships came to port in
Naples recently and Tuesday night chose Sorrento, a short ride
down the coast, to release their pent-up tensions.
</P>
<P>
Some 400 were reported to have gone on a pub crawl around
Sorrento's several English-style pubs and to have become deeply
drunk, causing confusion and some trepidation throughout the
night.
</P>
<P>
The two soldiers who went on a joy ride went to court Wednesday
and were given suspended eight-month jail sentences and fines of
one million lire (about 550 dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
