<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0343 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Athletic Group to Draw up Plan After Dismal World Champs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 1 (Xinhua)-- Athletics South Africa
ASA) is to formulate a plan to prevent a repeat of the dismal
performance by its World Championship team which returned to
Johannesburg on Wednesday with only one medal.
</P>
<P>
"We're going back to the drawing board," ASA CEO Banele Sindani
said. "We have to take stock of what happened and what did not
happen," he added, saying ASA would get more involved in athletes'
preparations ahead of major events.
</P>
<P>
"More involvement from ASA is needed. We are going to take an
active participation in an athlete's preparation... the full
content,"said Sindani, quoted by South African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
Sindani said the plan would be drawn up after talks with
coaches and athletes and would be unveiled by the end of October.
</P>
<P>
Team captain and South African 400m record-holder Arnaud
Malherbe said his problem had been over-racing -- a common
complaint by many of his team.
</P>
<P>
Although he had competed in both the local and European seasons
this year as he had in 1998 when he went on to perform well at the
Commonwealth Games, he had raced twice as often in Europe this
year.
</P>
<P>
"The financial incentives in Europe are big. I want to race the
Golden League next year. I need to cut my race numbers and it's
probably going to be in the South African season."
</P>
<P>
Malherbe said the maximum number of races in a year should be
20."I haven't counted yet (how many I have done), but it's over 30.
It's just too much."
</P>
<P>
Malherbe, however, was part of the 4x400m relay team which
broke the South African record and finished fourth. The men's
4x100m side also cracked a national mark.
</P>
<P>
But apart from those, all 44 athletes in the team failed to
achieve personal bests -- while many other competitors managed to
peak for the competition.
</P>
<P>
The ASA qualifying standards stipulated that athletes had to
compete at the national championships in Durban in March as well
as beat stipulated times and distances at that and other events.
</P>
<P>
Ironically, Hezekiel Sepeng boycotted nationals and was handed
a hefty fine for doing so.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 Olympic silver medalist who had said the World
Championships were not part of his preparations, was edged into
second place by Kenyan-born Wilson Kipketer for SA's sole medal.
</P>
<P>
At the previous World Championships in Athens in 1997, Marius
Corbett won javelin gold and Llewellyn Herbert silver in the 400m
hurdles.
</P>
<P>
But Herbert, the favorite to win this time around, pulled out
because of injury while an off-form Corbett fell way short of his
winning distance two years ago.
</P>
<P>
In spite of the lack of silverware, Malherbe was confident of a
much-improved showing at the All-Africa Games which start in
Johannesburg next week.
</P>
<P>
"Physically the team is very fit. Mentally we've learned a lot..
. I think we're going to have a good All-Africa Games."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
