<HEADLINE> Seaman Injury Blow for England </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- England's chances of reaching
the European Championship finals have suffered a major setback,
after first choice goalkeeper David Seaman followed Sol Campbell
out of the squad.
</P>
<P>
Arsenal star Seaman is still struggling with a calf injury and
will miss the clashes with Luxembourg on Saturday and Poland next
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But there was better news for manager Kevin Keegan when star
striker Michael Owen announced he would be able to last 90 minutes
in both England's vital qualifying matches.
</P>
<P>
Seaman, who picked up the injury in a pre-season game with St
Etienne, is the fourth player to pull out, after Campbell, Darren
Anderton and Rio Ferdinand.
</P>
<P>
Nigel Martyn of Leeds looks likely to replace him between the
posts in both matches - but Keegan may be tempted to call up
further goalkeeping cover.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Tottenham manager George Graham finally had his wish
granted with the withdrawal of central defender Campbell from
Keegan's squad.
</P>
<P>
According to local press, Graham was involved in a public
disagreement with Keegan over Campbell being made to link up with
the England squad when he felt there was no chance of his being
fit to play.
</P>
<P>
The Spurs boss had insisted all along that Campbell was unfit -
but Keegan wanted the England medical staff to assess the player
in case there was a chance of him recovering in time to face
Poland a week today.
</P>
<P>
That slim hope disappeared with Campbell, who has played just
25 minutes this season, being sent back to White Hart Lane.
</P>
<P>
Campbell has joined Tottenham team-mate Darren Anderton and
West Ham defender Rio Ferdinand in withdrawing from the two games
England must win to reach the Euro play-offs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
