<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0348 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prospect for Immediate Israeli, Palestinian Deal Slim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 2 (Xinhua) -- In what would be a major setback
in the peace process, Israel and the Palestinians failed to reach a
deal on implementing a U.S.-brokered peace accord Thursday, hours
before a tentatively planned signing ceremony in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
A lengthy meeting of Israel's inner cabinet ended early Thursday
morning without making a decision on the Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations over the implementation of the Wye accord. A new round
of talks planned to resume after the cabinet meeting was canceled.
</P>
<P>
The two sides might not be able to sign a memorandum on the
implementation of the Wye agreement in Alexandria, Egypt, Thursday
afternoon as widely expected, local media quoted sources close to
Prime Minister Ehud Barak as saying.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who started a four-day
visit to the region in Morocco Wednesday, had expected to attend the
signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
There would be a major frustration not only for both Israel and the
Palestinians, but for Albright, who might have to be involved in
mediating the disputes between the two sides, something Washington has
been trying to avoid since Barak took office in early July.
</P>
<P>
Washington has said that Albright's visit, which will also bring her to
Egypt, Israel, the Palestinian self-rule areas, Syria and Jordan, aims
to push forward the Israeli, Palestinian negotiations on the permanent
status and to resume the frozen Israeli-Syrian talks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators have intensified efforts in the
last few days to bridge their gaps over the implementation of the Wye
accord, signed and then frozen by Barak's hard-line predecessor
Benjamin Netanyahu last year.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday afternoon, the negotiations broke off without
reaching agreement on two remaining issues: the release of Palestinian
prisoners and a target date for a final status agreement.
</P>
<P>
After the gaps narrowed in rounds of talks lasting for over one
month, the Palestinians now demand that Israel release 400 political
prisoners, those jailed for anti-Israel activities. But Israel insists
that it will release only 350.
</P>
<P>
Israel proposed that the two sides reach a final status agreement
in December 2000, but the Palestinian wants the agreement to be
reached in April.
</P>
<P>
Barak's office issued a statement after the talks, declaring the
negotiations were over and threatening to carry out the original Wye
deal "to the letter," or according to Israeli interpretation, unless
the Palestinians came up with new proposals before the security
cabinet meeting starting at 7 p.m. (1600GMT).
</P>
<P>
For his part, senior Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat urged the
Israelis to continue talks and refrain from "any insinuation of an
ultimatum or threat, " saying he had sent new proposals to the Israeli
side on the issues where disputes exist.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli ultimatum, the second in the last few days, turned out
to be an attempt to make last-minute gains before the two sides
reached an agreement.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after Barak set the deadline, Haim Ramon, minister in the
Prime Minister's Office, held two hours of surprise talks with Erekat
in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Both sides emerged from the meeting in upbeat moods. Ramon said
every remaining problem would be resolved and Erekat said gaps had
been further narrowed by proposals Ramon brought to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
It was at this meeting that the two sides decided to resume the
negotiations as soon as the cabinet meeting concluded.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Barak had apologized to Arafat for the statement
insinuating an ultimatum.
</P>
<P>
Arafat cut short a visit to the Netherlands after a telephone
conversation with U.S. President Bill Clinton over the deadlock.
The Palestinian leader said earlier in The Hagues that he expected
a deal would be struck "in a few hours" although the talks hit a
snag.
</P>
<P>
Actually, the two sides have already been on the verge of an
agreement. In the previous talks, they have made significant progress
on most issues concerning the implementation of the Wye accord,
including a timeline of further Israeli troop withdrawals from the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Wye agreement calls on Israel to hand over 13 percent of the
West Bank to the Palestinians in three stages over a period of 12
weeks and release hundreds of Palestinian prisoners. Netanyahu froze
the deal after carrying out its first stage.
</P>
<P>
Ousting Netanyahu in the national elections three months ago on a
platform to revive the Middle East peace process on all its tracks,
Barak has promised to carry out the Wye agreement but proposed some
changes in its implementation.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have accepted his proposal to divide the two
remaining phases of Israeli troop withdrawals into three stages and
put off the final stage until early next year to avoid potential
confrontation between Palestinians and Jewish settlers.
</P>
<P>
About 15 Jewish settlements will be isolated, partially or fully,
after the final stage of troop withdrawals is carried out. Israel
wants to combine this stage into the final status talks, which aims at
a permanent peace between the two sides, in order to reduce the risk.
</P>
<P>
They have also agreed upon several sideline issues such as the
construction of a seaport in Gaza and the opening of safe passages
between Gaza and the West Bank. Israel has said that if the two sides
could not agree on all issues, it would carry out the Wye agreement as
written, meaning all understandings recently reached including those
on the seaport and safe passages would not be implemented. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990902.0349 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Banks: England's World Cup Bid not Affected by Hooligans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Former British Sports Minister
Tony Banks has scotched suggestions that hooligans will undermine
England's chances to host the World Cup in 2006.
</P>
<P>
The England's 2006 World Cup ambassador believes English clubs
have an impeccable record.
</P>
<P>
"There is only a problem in England if we close our eyes to
other parts of the world," Banks said at the launch of new soccer
finance book 'A Game of Two Halves'.
</P>
<P>
"The number of incidents here is nothing like in other
countries,it's just amplified under the magnifying glass of
scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
"There is no trouble worth mentioning inside our grounds and
that counts heavily with those who assess the bids."
</P>
<P>
There have been some incidents of late which raised a few
eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
West Ham supporters clashed with Metz fans in France during
their Intertoto final, and a fan did run onto the pitch at Chester
this week and tackle the referee.
</P>
<P>
And there is concern that Swedish hard men from AIK Solna,
drawn in Arsenal's Champions League group, will make life hard for
the English bid team, but Banks stands defiant.
</P>
<P>
He has every faith in FIFA's sense of fairness over the issue,
but is wary of other factors which could unsettle FIFA chiefs'
views as to the best bid.
</P>
<P>
"Fortunately FIFA have a wide overview of world football far
greater than that at home. They're more open minded about the
situation here," Banks said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
