<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Bounce Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks bounced
back Wednesday under the impetus of technology issues.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 108.60 at
10,937.88, ending a four-day fall since last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index rose 10.66 at 1,331.07 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index rose 11.45 at 2,750.80.
</P>
<P>
IBM was one of the strongest Dow stocks today after the
computer maker said Tuesday it will jointly with Cisco provide
networking equipment and services to companies looking to do
business online.
</P>
<P>
Intel pushed the Nasdaq index higher as it unveiled a new
microprocessor chip intended for use in devices that route
information across the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index rose 4.96 at 617.29 and the American Stock
Exchange index rose 7.78 at 783.19. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies rose 3.16 at 430.99.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,711 up, 1,293 down and 518
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 697.15 million shares from 838.48
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
