<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Leaves Hague For Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat left The Hague of the Netherlands Wednesday for Alexandria
of Egypt for a peace deal signing ceremony with Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader earlier told reporters in The Hague that
he hoped an eight-month deadlock with Israel over the Wye River
land-for-security agreement could be broken as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
At a doorstep interview with journalists in The Hague this
afternoon, Arafat made the statement after meeting with Dutch
Prime Minister Wim Kok and Foreign Minister Jozias van Aartsen,
but he declined to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
A Dutch foreign ministry spokesman said Arafat left because he
wants to get involved in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators resumed their talks late at
night in Jerusalem in a race to finalize revisions to the Wye
River deal, frozen since December.
</P>
<P>
They were said to try to overcome differences in time for a
Thursday afternoon signing in Alexandria in the presence of U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
